April. He noted that Fidesz had a realistic chance to win a landslide. Concerning the radical nationalist [[Jobbik]] party's gaining ground K\u00f6v\u00e9r said it was a \"lamentably negative\" tendency, adding that it was rooted in the ''\"disaster government\"'' of the Socialist Party and its former liberal ally Free Democrats.<ref>{{cite web |author=MTI |url=http://www.politics.hu/20100129/opposition-fidesz-aims-at-twothirds-majority |title=Opposition Fidesz aims at two-thirds majority |publisher=Politics.hu |accessdate=17 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311112636/http://www.politics.hu/20100129/opposition-fidesz-aims-at-twothirds-majority/ |archive-date=11 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===European Parliament===\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Election year\n! # of overall votes\n! % of overall vote\n! # of overall seats won\n! +/-\n! Notes\n|-\n! [[2004 European Parliament election in Hungary|2004]]\n| 1,457,750\n| 47.4% ('''1st''')\n| {{Composition bar|12|24|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| \n| \n|-\n! [[2009 European Parliament election in Hungary|2009]]<sup>1</sup>\n| 1,632,309\n| 56.36% ('''1st''')\n| {{Composition bar|13|22|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n|\n|-\n! [[2014 European Parliament election in Hungary|2014]]<sup>1</sup>\n| 1,193,991\n| 51.48% ('''1st''')\n| {{Composition bar|11|21|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 2\n|\n|-\n! [[2019 European Parliament election in Hungary|2019]]<sup>1</sup>\n| 1,824,220\n| 52.56% ('''1st''')\n| {{Composition bar|12|21|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n|\n|}\n<sup>1</sup> <small>Joint list with [[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|Christian Democratic People's Party]] (KDNP)</small>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{commons category|Fidesz}}\n*[http://www.fidesz.hu/ Fidesz \u2013 Hungarian Civic Union] Official website\n*[http://www.epp.eu/countryPg.asp?cid=12 Fidesz page on the website of the European People's Party]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060310004229/http://www.fideszfrakcio.hu/index.php?CikkID=10909&FIDESZSESSID=d777505ada9e30c9dc3a785cfa89d5a8 Speech delivered by Mr Viktor Orban at the 17th Congress of Fidesz upon his election as president of Fidesz \u2013 Hungarian Civic Union, 17 May 2003] (from Google's cache)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051129071015/http://www.fideszfrakcio.hu/index.php?CikkID=5350&FIDESZSESSID=3a4bab2f8242ecbeba363bf9fb8b1152 The History of Fidesz] (from Google's cache)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930185401/http://euronews.net/create_html.php?page=detail_info&article=383058&lng=1 Hungary's PM calls confidence vote]\n{{Hungarian political parties}}\n{{International Democrat Union}}\n{{European People's Party}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Fidesz| ]]\n[[Category:1988 establishments in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Eurosceptic parties in Hungary]]\n[[Category:International Democrat Union member parties]]\n[[Category:Member parties of the European People's Party]]\n[[Category:National conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Parties represented in the European Parliament]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Social conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Christian democratic parties in Europe]]\n[[Category:Christian political parties in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populist parties]]\n[[Category:Anti-communist parties]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Hungarian political party}}\n{{redirect |Hungarian Civic Party|the political party in Romania|Hungarian Civic Party (Romania)|the former political party in Slovakia|Hungarian Civic Party (Slovakia)}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Fidesz \u2013 Hungarian Civic Alliance\n| logo = Fidesz 2015.svg\n| colorcode = {{Fidesz/meta/color}}\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|df=y|1988|3|30}}\n| ideology = {{plainlist|\n*[[National conservatism]]<ref name= Nordsieck>{{cite web|url= http://parties-and-elections.eu/hungary.html|title=Hungary |last= Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|year= 2018 |website=Parties and Elections in Europe}}</ref><ref name=Hlou\u0161ekKope\u010dek/><ref name= \"Bakke\"/>\n*[[Social conservatism]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Buckley |first1=Neil |title=Orban drags Hungary through rapid change |url=https://www.ft.com/content/560076f6-32eb-11e0-9a61-00144feabdc0 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=7 February 2011 |accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Euroscepticism]]<ref>{{cite conference|last1=Horvath |first1=Attila |title=From Anti-communism to Anti-EUism: Faces of Fidesz's Euroscepticism |journal=University Association for Contemporary European Studies |year=2016 |conference=UACES 46th Annual Conference |url=https://www.uaces.org/events/conferences/london/papers/abstract.php?paper_id=148}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Heged\u00fcs |first1=Daniel |title=Can the right in East and West unite? |url=https://www.ips-journal.eu/regions/europe/article/show/can-the-right-in-east-and-west-unite-3499/ |accessdate=12 October 2019 |work=International Politics and Society |date=27 May 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Petsinis |first1=Vassilis |title=\u2019It is also the economy, stupid!\u2019 The rise of economic euroscepticism in Central and Eastern Europe |url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/can-europe-make-it/it-is-also-economy-stupid-rise-of-economic-euroscepticism-in-ce/ |accessdate=12 October 2019 |work=openDemocracy |date=23 February 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Anti-immigration]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andr\u00e1s |first1=B\u00edr\u00f3 |last2= Tam\u00e1s |first2=Boros |last3= \u00c1ron |first3= Varga |title= Euroszkepticizmus Magyarorsz\u00e1gon |url= http://www.policysolutions.hu/userfiles/elemzesek/Euroszkepticizmus%20Magyarorsz%C3%A1gon.pdf |website=Policy Solutions |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150906103039/http://www.policysolutions.hu/userfiles/elemzesek/Euroszkepticizmus%20Magyarorsz%C3%A1gon.pdf |archivedate=6 September 2015 |language= hu }}</ref>\n*[[Right-wing populism]]<ref name= Hlou\u0161ekKope\u010dek/><ref name= \"Bakke\"/><ref name= \"Bieling2015\">{{cite book| first = Hans-J\u00fcrgen | last = Bieling|chapter= Uneven development and 'European crisis constitutionalism', or the reasons for and conditions of a 'passive revolution in trouble'|editor1-first =Johannes | editor1-last = J\u00e4ger|editor2-first =Elisabeth | editor2-last = Springler|title= Asymmetric Crisis in Europe and Possible Futures: Critical Political Economy and Post-Keynesian Perspectives |chapter-url= https://books.google.com/books?id=JJsGCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 |year= 2015 |publisher=Routledge|isbn= 978-1-317-65298-4|page=110}}</ref>\n*[[Christian democracy]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sch\u00f6pflin |first1=Gy\u00f6rgy |title=Hungary: the Fidesz Project |url=https://www.aspenreview.com/article/2017/hungary%3A-the-fidesz-project/ |accessdate=12 October 2019 |work=[[Aspen Review Central Europe]] |issue=1 |year=2013}}</ref>\n*[[Economic nationalism]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Boz\u00f3ki |first1=Andr\u00e1s |editor1-last=Krasztev |editor1-first=P\u00e9ter |editor2-last=Van Til |editor2-first=Jon |title=The Hungarian Patient: Social Opposition to an Illiberal Democracy |date=2015 |publisher=[[Central European University Press]] |page=21 |chapter=Chapter 1: Broken Democracy, Predatory State, and Nationalist Populism}}</ref>}}\n| headquarters = 1088 [[Budapest]], VIII. Szentkir\u00e1lyi Street 18.\n| international = {{plainlist|\n* [[International Democrat Union]]\n*{{nowrap|[[Centrist Democrat International]]}}}}\n| website = {{URL|www.fidesz.hu/ |www.fidesz.hu}}\n| country = Hungary\n| native_name = Fidesz \u2013 Magyar Polg\u00e1ri Sz\u00f6vets\u00e9g\n| leader1_title = President\n| leader1_name = [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]]\n| leader2_title = Vice Presidents\n| leader2_name = {{plainlist|\n*[[Lajos K\u00f3sa]]\n*[[G\u00e1bor Kubatov]]\n*[[Szil\u00e1rd N\u00e9meth (politician)|Szil\u00e1rd N\u00e9meth]]\n*[[Katalin Nov\u00e1k]]}}\n| leader3_title = Parliamentary leader\n| leader3_name = [[M\u00e1t\u00e9 Kocsis]]\n| youth_wing = [[Fidelitas (Hungary)|Fidelitas]]\n| position = '''Present:'''<br>[[Right-wing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/sex-tapes-scandals-hungarys-local-election-campaign-66204348|title=Sex tapes, scandals in Hungary's local election campaign|quote=Borkai is running for re-election as mayor of the northwestern city of Gyor, representing Orban's right-wing Fidesz party. Another leaked sex video featured an opposition politician, Tamas Wittinghoff, the mayor of a town near Budapest.|work=abc news|date=11 October 2019}}</ref> to [[Far-right politics|far-right]]{{Efn |<ref name= Hlou\u0161ekKope\u010dek/><ref name= \"Bakke\"/><ref name= \"Bieling2015\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/16/world/europe/hungary-protests-viktor-orban.html|title=Opposition in Hungary Demonstrates Against Orban, in Rare Display of Dissent|last1=Kingsley|first1=Patrick|website=The New York Times|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/12/world/europe/hungary-courts.html|title=Hungary Creates New Court System, Cementing Leader's Control of Judiciary|last1=Novak|first1=Benjamin|last2=Kingsley|first2=Patrick|website=The New York Times|accessdate=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/michael-gove-viktor-orban-hungarian-government-far-right-a8540146.html|title=Michael Gove refuses to condemn far-right Hungarian leader Viktor Orban|last1=Cowburn|first1=Ashley|website=The Independent|accessdate=16 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/05/how-hungary-became-a-haven-for-the-alt-right/527178/|title=How Hungary Became a Haven for the Alt-Right|last1=Schaeffer|first1=Carol|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Why rightwing populism has radicalised|url=https://www.ft.com/content/0fcafba6-d428-11e9-8367-807ebd53ab77|first=Simon|last=Kuper|date=11 September 2019|website=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=The Hungarian paradigm shift: how right-wing are Fidesz supporters?|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/can-europe-make-it/hungarian-paradigm-shift-how-right-wing-are-fidesz-supporters/|first=Katherine|last=Kondor|date=30 January 2019|website=[[openDemocracy]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Viktor Orb\u00e1n's Far-Right Vision for Europe|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/01/14/viktor-orbans-far-right-vision-for-europe|first=Elisabeth|last=Zerofsky|date=7 January 2019|website=[[The New Yorker]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Hungary's Far-Right Government Has Been Getting a Boost from President Trump Ahead of E.U. Elections|url=https://time.com/5590134/hungary-foreign-minister-interview/|first=Vivienne|last=Walt|date=22 May 2019|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Hungarian opposition party says its meetings in parliament were bugged|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/hugary-p-rbesz-d-spy-recordings-bugged-gergely-kar-csony-a9126441.html|quote=Hungarian politics is dominated by Viktor Orban's far-right Fidesz party, which is supported by a largely partisan pro-government media that marginalises opposition voices.|first=Jon|last=Stone|date=30 September 2019|website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/9/13/17823488/hungary-democracy-authoritarianism-trump|title=It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary|last1=Beauchamp|first1=Zack|work=Vox|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Hungary's prime minister stole the country's democracy. Now Hungarians are rising up.\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2018/12/17/18144648/hungary-protest-orban-labor-democracy|title=Hungary's prime minister stole the country's democracy. Now Hungarians are rising up.|last1=Beauchamp|first1=Zack|work=Vox|date=17 December 2018|accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/20/world/europe/orban-epp.html|title=Top E.U. Coalition Suspends Party Led by Orban, Hungary's Leader|last=Santora|first=Marc|date=20 March 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=29 May 2019|last2=Erlanger|first2=Steven|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/04/viktor-orban-hungary/557246/|title=The Most Dangerous Man in the European Union|last=Lendvai|first=Paul|date=7 April 2018|website=The Atlantic|access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref>}}<br>'''Formerly:'''<br>{{Nowrap|[[Centre-right]]<ref>{{cite news |date= 26 May 1998 |title= Stunning win for centre-right Fidesz party |url= https://www.irishtimes.com/news/stunning-win-for-centre-right-fidesz-party-1.156754 |work= The Irish Times |access-date= 2 October 2019}}</ref> to [[right-wing]]<ref>{{Citation |url= https://www.economist.com/blogs/dailychart/2010/12/fidesz |newspaper=The Economist |title= Fidesz: The story so far |date= 18 December 2010 |accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |url= http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/right-wing-fidesz-party-wins-by-landslide-in-hungary-elections/story-e6frfku0-1225852566022 |first=Balint |last= Seres |newspaper= News AU |title=Right-wing Fidesz party wins by landslide in Hungary elections |date=12 April 2010 |accessdate= 18 November 2011|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]}}</ref>}}\n| national = [[Fidesz\u2013KDNP]]\n| european = [[European People's Party]] (suspended)<ref name=\"Fid-EPP\">{{cite news|title= Hungary's Orb\u00e1n clings on to Europe's power center|url= https://www.politico.eu/article/orbans-party-suspended-from-european-peoples-party/ |accessdate= 21 March 2019|date= 21 March 2019|work=Politico|last1=de la Baume|first1=Ma\u00efa|last2=Bayer|first2=Lili}}</ref>\n| europarl = [[European People's Party group|European People's Party]]\n| seats1_title = [[National Assembly (Hungary)|National Assembly]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar |117|199|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|12|21|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Counties of Hungary|County Assemblies]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar |245|419|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| colours = {{Color box |{{Fidesz/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} Orange\n| flag = [[File:Flag of Fidesz (Hungary).svg|border|200px]]\n}}\n'''Fidesz \u2013 Hungarian Civic Alliance''' ({{IPA-hu |\u02c8fid\u025bs}}; in full, {{lang-hu|Fidesz \u2013 Magyar Polg\u00e1ri Sz\u00f6vets\u00e9g}}) is a [[national conservatism|national-conservative]],<ref name= Nordsieck/><ref name= Hlou\u0161ekKope\u010dek/><ref name= \"Bakke\" /> [[Right-wing populism|right-wing populist]]<ref name= Hlou\u0161ekKope\u010dek>{{Citation |first1= V\u00edt |last1=Hlou\u0161ek |first2= Lubom\u00edr |last2=Kope\u010dek |title= Origin, Ideology and Transformation of Political Parties: East-Central and Western Europe Compared |publisher= Ashgate |year= 2010 |page= 115}}</ref><ref name= \"Bakke\">{{Citation |first=Elisabeth |last=Bakke |title= Central and East European party systems since 1989 |work= Central and Southeast European Politics Since 1989 |publisher= Cambridge University Press |year= 2010 |page=79 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=oFXdiS25N78C&pg=PA79 |accessdate= 17 November 2011|isbn= 978-1-13948750-4}}</ref><ref name= \"Bieling2015\"/> [[list of political parties in Hungary|political party]] in Hungary.\n\nFounded in 1988 as a liberal youth party opposing the ruling communist government, Fidesz has come to dominate Hungarian politics on the national and local level since its landslide victory in the [[2010 Hungarian parliamentary election|2010 national elections]] on a joint list with the [[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|Christian Democratic People's Party]],{{Efn | Fidesz had common regional and nationwide lists and had common candidates with [[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|KDNP]] in the 2010 and 2014 elections.}} securing it a parliamentary [[supermajority]] that it retained [[2014 Hungarian parliamentary election|in 2014]]<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\">{{cite web|url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/hungarys-ruling-party-loses-two-thirds-majority-after-by-election-1424634646|title=Hungary's Ruling Party Loses Two-Thirds Majority after By-Election| work =The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref><ref name= \"Index.hu\">{{cite news|last1= Dull |first1=Szabolcs|title= Gy\u0151z\u00f6tt a Jobbik a tapolcai v\u00e1laszt\u00e1son |url= http://index.hu/belfold/2015/04/12/idokozi_valasztas_ajka_sumeg_tapolca_parlament/ |accessdate= 12 April 2015|publisher= Index HU}}</ref> and again [[2018 Hungarian parliamentary election|in 2018]].<ref>{{cite news|last1= Bayer |first1=Lili|title=Orb\u00e1n poised to tighten grip on power |url= https://www.politico.eu/article/viktor-orban-fidesz-poised-to-tighten-grip-on-power-hungary-budapest-election/|accessdate= 10 April 2018|work=Politico |date= 10 April 2018}}</ref> Fidesz also enjoys majorities in the [[Counties of Hungary|county legislatures]] (19 of 19), but it only has majorities in (10 of 23) assemblies in the cities with county rights and is currently in a minority (13 of 33) in the [[2019 Budapest Assembly election|Budapest assembly]]. [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] has been the leader of the party for most of its history.\n\n==History==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== 1980s: Activist beginnings ===\nThe party was founded in the Spring of 1988,{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} named ''Fiatal Demokrat\u00e1k Sz\u00f6vets\u00e9ge'', meaning the ''Alliance of Young Democrats,'' abbr. ''FIDESZ''. Growing out of an underground [[classical liberal|liberal]] student activist movement opposing to the ruling [[Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party|communist party]].<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.politico.eu/article/ties-that-bind-hungarys-fidesz-and-european-parliament/|title=Ties that bind Hungary's Fidesz and European Parliament|work= Politico}}</ref><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> Founding such a movement was half-illegal at that time, so the founders risked their careers by being involved in the opposition. The membership had an upper age limit of 35 years (this requirement was abolished at the [[1993 party congress]]).{{Citation needed |date=March 2019}}\n\nIn 1989, Fidesz won the [[Rafto Prize]]. The movement was represented at the award ceremony by one of its leaders, [[P\u00e9ter Moln\u00e1r (academic)|P\u00e9ter Moln\u00e1r]], who later became a Member of [[National Assembly (Hungary)|Parliament]] in Hungary.{{Citation needed|date= March 2019}}\n\n=== 1990\u20131998: In opposition, conservative turn ===\nIn the 1990 elections the party could get into the National Assembly with a result of about 6%. They became a small, though quite popular [[Parliamentary opposition|oppositional]] party. In 1992, Fidesz joined the [[Liberal International]].<ref name=\"History of Fidesz\" /> At that time, it was a moderate liberal centrist party. \n\nAt the 1993 party congress they changed their political position from liberal to [[Centrism|civic-centrist]] (\"polg\u00e1ri centrump\u00e1rt\"). The turn in ideology caused a severe split in the membership. [[P\u00e9ter Moln\u00e1r (academic)|P\u00e9ter Moln\u00e1r]] left the party, as well as [[G\u00e1bor Fodor (politician)|G\u00e1bor Fodor]] and Kl\u00e1ra Ung\u00e1r, who joined the liberal [[Alliance of Free Democrats]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} Viktor Orb\u00e1n was elected the chairman of the party.  \n\nAfter its disappointing result in the [[1994 Hungarian parliamentary election|1994 elections]], Fidesz remained an oppositional party, however more and more conservative.<ref name=\"Bakke\" /><ref name=\"History of Fidesz\">[http://www.fidesz.hu/index.php?Cikk=68476]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010152354/http://www.fidesz.hu/index.php?Cikk=68476|date=10 October 2007}}</ref> \n\nIn 1995, it changed its name to ''Hungarian Civic Party'' (''Magyar Polg\u00e1ri P\u00e1rt'') and sought connection to the former [[Hungarian Democratic Forum|governing parties]].\n\n=== 1998\u20132002: The first Orb\u00e1n government ===\nFidesz gained power at the [[1998 Hungarian parliamentary election|1998 elections]]. Viktor Orb\u00e1n became prime minister. Their [[Coalition government|coalition]] partners were the smaller [[Hungarian Democratic Forum]] and the [[Independent Smallholders, Agrarian Workers and Civic Party|Independent Smallholders' Party]]. In 2000, Fidesz terminated its membership in the Liberal International and joined the [[European People's Party]].<ref name=\"History of Fidesz\"/> The government constituted a \"relatively conventional European conservative\" rule.<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />\n\n=== 2002\u20132010: Return to opposition ===\n[[File:Budapest heroes Fidesz HQ.jpg|thumb|left|The former main office building of Fidesz]]\nFidesz narrowly lost the [[2002 Hungarian parliamentary election|2002 elections]] to the [[Hungarian Socialist Party]], garnering 41.07% to the Socialists' 42.05%. Fidesz had 169 members of the [[Hungarian National Assembly]], out of a total of 386. Immediately after the election, they accused the opponents of [[electoral fraud]].<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> The 2002 Hungarian municipal election saw again huge Fidesz losses.{{Citation needed|date= March 2019}}\n\nIn the spring of 2003, Fidesz took its current name, ''Fidesz \u2013 Hungarian Civic Union''.<ref name=\"History of Fidesz\" />\n\nIt was the most successful party in the [[2004 European Parliament election in Hungary|2004 European Parliamentary Elections]]: it won 47.4% of the vote and 12 of its candidates were elected as [[Member of the European Parliament|Members of the European Parliament]] (MEPs), including [[L\u00edvia J\u00e1r\u00f3ka]], the second [[Romani people|Romani]] MEP.{{Citation needed |date= March 2019}}\n\n{{Clarify|reason=Poor grammar (is?, was?). Appears outdated \u2013 as of when? Source date is 2005. Also, \"regarded as a success\" would be more impartial\u2026 |date= March 2019|text=The election of Dr. L\u00e1szl\u00f3 S\u00f3lyom as the new President of Hungary as the most recent success of the party.}}  He was endorsed by [[V\u00e9degylet NGO|V\u00e9degylet]], an NGO including people from the whole political spectrum. His activity does not entirely overlap with the conservative ideals and he championed for elements of both political wings with a selective, but conscious choice of values.<ref>{{in lang|hu}} [http://index.hu/politika/belfold/kernt8094/ S\u00f3lyom politikaform\u00e1l\u00f3 er\u0151 akar lenni], Kern Tam\u00e1s, [[Index.hu]], 22 August 2005</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Fidesz and the [[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|Christian Democratic People's Party]] (KDNP) formed an alliance for the [[2006 Hungarian parliamentary election|2006 elections]]. Despite winning 42.0% of the list votes and 164 representatives out of 386 in [[National Assembly of Hungary|National Assembly]], they were beaten by the social-democratic and liberal coalition of [[Hungarian Socialist Party]] (MSZP) and the [[Alliance of Free Democrats]] (SZDSZ).{{Citation needed|date= March 2019}}\n\nOn 1 October 2006 Fidesz won the municipal elections, which counterbalanced the MSZP-led government's power to some extent. Fidesz won 15 of 23 mayoralties in Hungary's largest cities\u2014although its candidate narrowly lost the city of Budapest to a member of the Liberal Party\u2014and majorities in 18 out of 20 regional assemblies.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.vokscentrum.hu/onkorm/elemzo.php?jny=hun&mszkod=860001&mitmut=polgmjv |title= VoksCentrum a v\u00e1laszt\u00e1sok univerzuma |publisher= Vokscentrum |accessdate= 17 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070818083027/http://www.vokscentrum.hu/onkorm/elemzo.php?jny=hun&mszkod=860001&mitmut=polgmjv |archivedate= 18 August 2007}}</ref><ref name= OctElects06>{{cite web |url= http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2006/10/03/2003330242 |title=Opposition makes substantial gains in Hungarian elections | work = Taipei Times |date=29 August 2015 |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2009 European Parliament election in Hungary|2009 European Parliament election]], Fidesz won a landslide victory, gaining 56.36% of the vote and 14 of Hungary's 22 seats.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nIn a closed-door party meeting in 2009, Orb\u00e1n called for a \"central political forcefield\" to govern Hungary for up to 20 years to achieve political stability.<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />\n\n=== 2010\u2013: In power ===\nThe strong and preeminent Fidesz has benefited from the fragmented and disjointed opposition that has proved inept at mounting a unified challenge to the ruling party in a country where a majority of parliamentary seats are allocated to the party that garners the plurality of votes in a constituency.<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/25/world/europe/hungary-election-viktor-orban.html|title=In Hungary, Disunity and Gerrymandering Frustrate Anti-Orban Voters|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=25 March 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===== Economy =====\nGovernment debt has fallen by 6% in the 8 years after Fidesz took power in 2010 while the country's credit ratings have improved. Economic growth had almost quadrupled with wages rising by over 10% and destitution decreasing by almost 50% (though still considerable). According to official figures, unemployment had fallen by nearly two-thirds. However, as many as almost half of newly employed Hungarians had found work elsewhere in the EU. A public works program has also been criticized by some economists for artificially and deceptively reducing unemployment numbers while engaging in and compensating people for possibly unneeded or unnecessarily inefficient work.<ref name=\":31\" />\n\nHungary has been highly dependent on EU funds during Fidesz's rule; these representing nearly 4% of the country's GDP, more than for any other EU member.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\n==== 2010\u20132014: Second Orb\u00e1n government ====\nIn a landslide victory in the [[2010 Hungarian parliamentary election|2010 parliamentary elections]], the party won an outright majority in the first round on 11 April, with the Fidesz-KDNP alliance winning 206 seats, including 119 individual seats. In the final result, Fidesz 263 seats, of which 173 are individual seats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.valasztas.hu/hu/parval2010/354/354_0_index.html |title=Orsz\u00e1gos V\u00e1laszt\u00e1si Iroda \u2013 2010 Orsz\u00e1ggy\u0171l\u00e9si V\u00e1laszt\u00e1sok |language=hu |publisher=Valasztas.hu |date=3 May 2010 |accessdate=5 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327031022/http://www.valasztas.hu/hu/parval2010/354/354_0_index.html |archive-date=27 March 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Fidesz held 227 of these seats, giving it an outright majority in the National Assembly by itself.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nFidesz was widely seen as propelled to a sweeping victory in large part due to the dissatisfaction with the ruling political establishment which was plagued by corruption scandals and suffered a further blow by the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|global financial crisis]].<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> The [[Hungarian Socialist Party|Socialist]] government had also imposed harsh austerity measures in an attempt to reign in its ballooning budget deficits even before the global crisis. In September 2006, a recording of the prime minister admitting to lying about the country's dire economic prospects was revealed by the media and broadcast on radio. Steel barriers were erected around Parliament to protect it from tens of thousands of protesters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/22/world/europe/foes-of-hungarys-government-fear-demolition-of-democracy.html|title=Foes of Hungary's Government Fear \u2018Demolition of Democracy\u2019|last=Kulish|first=Nicholas|date=21 December 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=16 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAfter winning 53% of the [[2010 Hungarian parliamentary election|popular vote in the first-round of the 2010 parliamentary election]], which translated into a [[supermajority]] of 68% of parliamentary seats, giving Fidesz sufficient power to revise or replace the constitution, the party embarked on an extraordinary project of passing over 200 laws and drafting and adopting a new constitution\u2014since followed by nearly 2000 amendments.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nThe [[Constitution of Hungary|new constitution]] has been widely criticized<ref>[https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/19/hungarys-constitutional-revolution/]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111220074218/http://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/12/19/hungarys-constitutional-revolution/|date=20 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-%2F%2FEP%2F%2FNONSGML%2BCOMPARL%2BPE-491.186%2B02%2BDOC%2BPDF%2BV0%2F%2FEN |format=PDF |title=Working Document 1 |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meetdocs/2009_2014/documents/libe/dv/906/906320/906320en.pdf |title=Working Document 2 |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-%2F%2FEP%2F%2FNONSGML%2BCOMPARL%2BPE-500.583%2B01%2BDOC%2BPDF%2BV0%2F%2FEN |format=PDF |title=Working Document 3 |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-%2F%2FEP%2F%2FNONSGML%2BCOMPARL%2BPE-502.280%2B01%2BDOC%2BPDF%2BV0%2F%2FEN |format=PDF |title=Working Document 4 |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.venice.coe.int/webforms/documents/by_opinion.aspx?country=17|title=Documents by opinions and studies|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref> by the [[Venice Commission]] for Democracy through Law,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lapa.princeton.edu/hosteddocs/hungary/venice%20commission%20hungarian%20constitution.pdf |title=EUROPEAN COMMISSION FOR DEMOCRACY THROUGH LAW (VENICE COMMISSION) : OPINION |publisher=Lapa.princeton.edu |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref> the [[Council of Europe]], the [[European Parliament]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//TEXT+TA+P7-TA-2011-0315+0+DOC+XML+V0//EN&language=EN |title=Texts adopted \u2013 Tuesday, 5 July 2011 \u2013 Revised Hungarian constitution \u2013 P7_TA(2011)0315 |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=4 September 2015}}</ref> and the United States<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hungary.usembassy.gov/kounalakis12082011.html |title=Remarks & Statements &#124; Budapest, Hungary \u2013 Embassy of the United States |publisher=Hungary.usembassy.gov |date=8 December 2011 |accessdate=4 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018221107/http://hungary.usembassy.gov/kounalakis12082011.html |archivedate=18 October 2015 }}</ref> for concentrating too much power in the hands of the ruling party, for limiting oversight of the new constitution by the [[Constitutional Court of Hungary]], and for removing democratic [[Separation of powers|checks and balances]] in various areas, including the ordinary [[judiciary]],<ref>[http://esbalogh.typepad.com/hungarianspectrum/2011/12/the-end-of-the-independent-judiciary.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313232727/http://esbalogh.typepad.com/hungarianspectrum/2011/12/the-end-of-the-independent-judiciary.html|date=13 March 2012}}</ref> supervision of elections, and the [[Freedom of the press|media]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nIn October 2013 [[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]], Secretary General of the Council of Europe said that the Council were satisfied with the amendments which had been made to the criticized laws.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ferenckumin.tumblr.com/post/63454622999/council-of-europes-jagland-hungarians-have-gone-a|title=Ferenc Kumin \u2013 Council of Europe's Jagland: 'Hungarians Have Gone...|publisher=Ferenckumin.tumblr.com|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== 2014\u20132018: Third Orb\u00e1n government ====\nFidesz won the [[2014 Hungarian parliamentary election|nationwide parliamentary election in April 2014]] and secured a second supermajority with 133 seats (of 199) in the legislature. This supermajority was lost, however, when [[Tibor Navracsics]] was appointed to the [[European Commission]]. His [[Veszpr\u00e9m county]] seat was taken by an independent candidate in a by-election.<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\"/> Another by-election on 12 April 2015 saw the supermajority lose a second seat, also in Veszpr\u00e9m, to a [[Jobbik]] candidate.<ref name=\"Index.hu\"/>\n\n==== 2018\u2013: Fourth Orb\u00e1n government ====\nFidesz won the [[2018 Hungarian parliamentary election|nationwide parliamentary election in April 2018]] and secured a 3rd supermajority with 133 seats (of 199) in the legislature. Orb\u00e1n and Fidesz campaigned primarily on the issues of immigration and foreign meddling, and the election was seen as a victory for [[right-wing populism]] in Europe.<ref name=\"OrbanReuters\">{{cite web | last1=Than | first1=Krisztina | last2=Szakacs | first2=Gergely | title=Hungary's Strongman Viktor Orban Wins Third Term in Power | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-election/hungarys-strongman-viktor-orban-wins-third-term-in-power-idUSKBN1HE0UC | date=9 April 2018 | agency=Reuters | accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"OrbanEUobserver\">{{cite web | last1=Zalan | first1=Eszter | title=Hungary's Orban in Sweeping Victory, Boosting EU Populists | url=https://euobserver.com/political/141539 | date=9 April 2018 | work=[[EUobserver]] | accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"MurphyKheraToI\">{{cite web | last1=Murphy | first1=Peter | last2=Khera | first2=Jastinder | title=Hungary's Orban Claims Victory as Nationalist Party Takes Sweeping Poll Lead | url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/hungarys-orban-claims-victory-as-nationalist-party-takes-sweeping-poll-lead/ | date=9 April 2018 | work=[[The Times of Israel]] | accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nWith the start of 2019, the prime minister's residence was relocated from the [[Hungarian Parliament Building]] to the [[Buda Castle]], a former [[Carmelites|Carmelite]] monastery and former royal residence. The move first planned in 2002 during the first Fidesz government, but was never carried out. Government representatives stated the move was necessary to uphold the separation of the executive and legislative branch by physically separating the two (in contrast to the communist era when the two branches operated in the same building) while the opposition criticized the move as profligate (the renovation cost Ft21bn (\u20ac65.5M)) and as a symbolic revival of the Horthy era ([[Mikl\u00f3s Horthy]] also took up residence in the building).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hungarytoday.hu/pm-moving-to-buda-castle-puritanism-in-a-former-monastery-or-costly-reminiscence-of-horthy-era/|title=PM Moving to Buda Castle: Puritanism in a Former Monastery or Costly Restoration of the Horthy Era?|date=7 January 2019|website=Hungary Today|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042855508|title=Orban se z novim letom seli v kraljevo pala\u010do|website=Dnevnik|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Ideology and policies==\nFidesz's position on the political spectrum has changed over time. At its inception as a student movement in the late-1980s, the party supported social and economic liberalism and [[European integration]]. As the Hungarian political landscape crystallized following the [[end of communism in Hungary (1989)|fall of communism]] and the [[1990 Hungarian parliamentary election|first free elections]], Fidesz began moving to the right. Although Fidesz was in opposition to the [[Hungarian Democratic Forum]]'s national-conservative coalition government from 1990 to 1994, by 1998 Fidesz was the most prominent conservative political force in Hungary.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nFidesz is currently considered a [[national conservative]] party favoring interventionist policies on economic issues like handling of banks, and a strong [[Social conservatism|conservative]] stance on social issues and [[European integration]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/8491837|title=Europe.view: Stars and soggy bottoms |work=The Economist|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fenteslent.blog.hu/2013/12/05/hegedus_zsuzsa_orban_igazi_szocialdemokrata|title=Heged\u0171s Zsuzsa: Orb\u00e1n igazi szoci\u00e1ldemokrata|work=Fent \u00e9s lent \u2013 g\u00e1tl\u00e1stalan patriotizmus|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.opendemocracy.net/gell\u00e9rt-rajcs\u00e1nyi/democracy-in-hungary-defence-of-fidesz]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504110055/http://www.opendemocracy.net/gell%C3%A9rt-rajcs%C3%A1nyi/democracy-in-hungary-defence-of-fidesz|date=4 May 2014}}</ref> Recently, the party has increasingly been described as far-right,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/16/world/europe/hungary-protests-viktor-orban.html|title=Opposition in Hungary Demonstrates Against Orban, in Rare Display of Dissent|last1=Kingsley|first1=Patrick|website=The New York Times|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/12/world/europe/hungary-courts.html|title=Hungary Creates New Court System, Cementing Leader's Control of Judiciary|last1=Novak|first1=Benjamin|last2=Kingsley|first2=Patrick|website=The New York Times|accessdate=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/michael-gove-viktor-orban-hungarian-government-far-right-a8540146.html|title=Michael Gove refuses to condemn far-right Hungarian leader Viktor Orban|last1=Cowburn|first1=Ashley|website=The Independent|accessdate=16 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/05/how-hungary-became-a-haven-for-the-alt-right/527178/|title=How Hungary Became a Haven for the Alt-Right|last1=Schaeffer|first1=Carol|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref> and its ruling style has also been variously described as \"soft [[fascist|fascism]]\",<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /><ref name=\"Hungary's prime minister stole the country's democracy. Now Hungarians are rising up.\" /> \"soft dictatorship\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/20/world/europe/orban-epp.html|title=Top E.U. Coalition Suspends Party Led by Orban, Hungary's Leader|last=Santora|first=Marc|date=20 March 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=29 May 2019|last2=Erlanger|first2=Steven|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and \"soft [[autocracy]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2018/04/viktor-orban-hungary/557246/|title=The Most Dangerous Man in the European Union|last=Lendvai|first=Paul|date=7 April 2018|website=The Atlantic|access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref> The Fidesz party has denied such accusations and distanced itself from the extreme right;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/ruling-hungarian-fidesz-party-adopts-policies-of-far-right-jobbik-party-a-880590.html|title=Hungarian Leader Adopts Policies of Far-Right|last1=Verseck|first1=Keno|website=Der Spiegel|accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref> it has criticized such accusations as politically motivated opposition to its [[anti-immigrant]] policies and pursuit of \"[[illiberal democracy]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-orban/hungarian-pm-sees-shift-to-illiberal-christian-democracy-in-2019-european-vote-idUSKBN1KI0BK|title=Hungarian PM sees shift to illiberal Christian democracy in 2019 European vote|agency=Reuters|accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/eu-parliament-votes-to-trigger-article-7-sanctions-procedure-against-hungary/a-45459720|title=EU Parliament votes to trigger Article 7 sanctions procedure against Hungary|last1=Staudenmaier|first1=Rebecca|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=12 September 2018|accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Korkut|first1=Umut|title=Resentment and Reorganization: Anti-Western Discourse and the Making of Eurasianism in Hungary|url=http://src-h.slav.hokudai.ac.jp/publictn/acta/38/Korkut.pdf|journal=Acta Slavica Iaponica|volume=38|pages=71\u201390}}</ref>\n\n=== Illiberal democracy ===\nOrb\u00e1n and other Fidesz politicians have prominently described their model of government as a Christian [[illiberal democracy]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-orban-idUSKBN1KI0BK|title=Hungarian PM sees shift to illiberal Christian democracy in 2019...|date=28 July 2018|agency=Reuters|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/25/world/europe/hungary-democracy-orban.html|title=On the Surface, Hungary Is a Democracy. But What Lies Underneath?|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=25 December 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=16 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Orb\u00e1n has described [[liberal democracy]] as having undemocratic characteristics because of \"being intolerant of alternative views\"<ref name=\":3\" /> and incompatible with and antithetical to Christian democracy,<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> and listed Turkey, Russia, China, and Singapore as successful examples of illiberal states.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/08/world/europe/viktor-orban-steers-hungary-toward-russia-25-years-after-fall-of-the-berlin-wall.html|title=Viktor Orban Steers Hungary Toward Russia 25 Years After Fall of the Berlin Wall|last=Lyman|first=Rick|date=7 November 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=16 March 2019|last2=Smale|first2=Alison|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/14/world/europe/viktor-orban-hungary-elections.html|title=Elections in Hungary Tighten Prime Minister's Hold on Power|last=Lyman|first=Rick|date=13 October 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=16 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Economy ===\n''See also:'' [[Orbanomics]]\n\nLike the Hungarian right in general, Fidesz has been more skeptical of the [[Neoliberal economics|neoliberal economic]] policies than the Hungarian left: according to researchers, the elites of the Hungarian left ([[MSzP]] and the former [[SZDSZ]]) have been differentiated from the right by being more supportive of the [[Classical liberalism|classical liberal]] economic policies, while the right (especially extreme right) has advocated more [[Economic interventionism|interventionist]] policies. In contrast, on issues like [[church and state]] and family policies, the liberals show alignment along the traditional left-right spectrum.<ref>Bodan Todosijevi\u0107 ''The Hungarian Voter: Left\u2013Right Dimension as a Clue to Policy Preferences'' in International Political Science Review (2004), Vol 25, No. 4, p. 421</ref> However, Fidesz has implemented several liberal economic policies, including a flat income tax, reductions in the corporate tax rate, restrictions on unemployment benefits, and privatisation of state-owned land.<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=3 April 2018|title=RPT-As Hungary roars ahead, Orbanomics leaves some of the poorest behind|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/hungary-election-economy/rpt-as-hungary-roars-ahead-orbanomics-leaves-some-of-the-poorest-behind-idUSL5N1RG265}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Financial Times]]|title=Hungary to offer EU's lowest corporate tax rate|date=17 November 2016|url=https://www.ft.com/content/302fa4b4-acda-11e6-9cb3-bb8207902122}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Budapest Beacon]]|title=Tiborcz and M\u00e9sz\u00e1ros families big winners in Fej\u00e9r county land privatization\n|url=https://budapestbeacon.com/tiborcz-meszaros-families-big-winners-fejer-county-land-privatization/|date=5 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Fidesz government has embraced a populist economic policy, including \"public works job program, pension hikes, utility bill cuts, a minimum wage increase and cash gifts for retirees\".<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/new-communists-hungary-poland-viktor-orban-jaroslaw-kaczynski/|title=The new communists|last=Bayer|first=Lili|date=5 April 2018|work=Politico|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> It has also implemented a national public works program<ref name=\":31\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/03/world/europe/viktor-orban-hungary-economy-election.html|title=An Economic Miracle in Hungary, or Just a Mirage?|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=3 April 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|last2=Novak|first2=Benjamin|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> aimed in particular at assisting neglected rural communities.<ref name=\"Santora\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/07/world/europe/hungary-viktor-orban-election.html|title=Orban Campaigns on Fear, With Hungary's Democracy at Stake|last=Santora|first=Marc|date=7 April 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It has sought national control of key economic sectors while assuming a cautious stance on economic globalisation.<ref name=\":25\" />\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\n\n==== European Union ====\nDespite the conflict with the [[European People's Party]] and [[European Union]] institutions, Fidesz and the Orb\u00e1n government have remained determinedly pro-European. Orb\u00e1n has on multiple occasions presented himself as not in conflict with but a manifestation of pan-European values. As he struggled to maintain rapport with the EPP, Orb\u00e1n began forming a right-wing populist alliance to electorally challenge the conservative EU establishment despite voicing a desire for Fidesz to remain a member.<ref name=\":9\"/><ref name=\"Reuters\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-eu-epp-idUSKCN1QM1MZ|title=European conservative gives ultimatum to Hungarian leader|date=5 March 2019|agency=Reuters|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> Orb\u00e1n and his government have clashed with the EU over the handling of the [[European migrant crisis]] and the death penalty (which is prohibited by EU rules).<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/11/world/europe/viktor-orban-european-peoples-party.html|title=E.U.\u2019s Leadership Seeks to Contain Hungary's Orban|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=11 September 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/apr/30/eu-jean-claude-juncker-viktor-orban-hungary-death-penalty-return|title=EU chief warns Hungary over return of death penalty comments|last=Traynor|first=Ian|date=30 April 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=13 March 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==== Russia and Ukraine ====\nFidesz-led Hungary was the only EU member state to vote against financial aid for Ukraine during its conflict with Russia-sponsored separatists, and has been a vocal critic of EU sanctions against Russia for its actions in Ukraine.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/09/hungary-relationship-russia-send-message-eu-180919131248490.html|title=Does Hungary's relationship with Russia send a message to the EU?|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> The main cause is that since 2017, [[Hungary\u2013Ukraine relations|relations with Ukraine]] rapidly deteriorated over the issue of the [[Hungarians in Ukraine|Hungarian minority in Ukraine]]. Hungary has been obstructing Ukraine's integration efforts in the European Union and NATO even though Hungary has also been continuously helping and supporting Ukraine, with an exceptional attention to [[Zakarpattia Oblast|Transcarpathia]].<ref>\"[https://www.neweurope.eu/article/hungary-ukraine-relations-hit-new-low-troop-deployment/ Hungary-Ukraine relations hit new low over troop deployment]\". ''[[New Europe (newspaper)|New Europe]]''. 26 March 2018.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/hungary-again-blocks-nato-ukraine-commission-vows-to-continue.html|title=Hungary again blocks NATO-Ukraine Commission, vows to continue \u2013 KyivPost \u2013 Ukraine's Global Voice|date=3 October 2018|website=Kyiv Post}}</ref><ref>https://magyaridok.hu/kulfold/szijjarto-peter-magyarorszag-aranyos-valaszt-ad-ukrajnanak-ha-kiutasitanak-a-konzult-3508439/</ref> Orb\u00e1n has \"strongly\" criticized EU sanctions against Russia, but abstained from vetoing them. The Fidesz government joined the UK-led diplomatic offensive after the [[Skripal poisoning]], expelling Russian embassy officials. Orb\u00e1n has hailed Russia as an exemplary case of \"illiberal democracy\".<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|last1=Janjevic |first1=Darko |title=Vladimir Putin and Viktor Orban's special relationship |url=https://www.dw.com/en/vladimir-putin-and-viktor-orbans-special-relationship/a-45512712 |accessdate=12 October 2019 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his presidency, Orb\u00e1n has been described as \"drawing closer to President Vladimir V. Putin\".<ref name=\":9\"/> The closer relationship between the two leaders and nations has however largely been motivated by a tighter economic relationship,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> part of the government's \"Eastern Opening\" strategy, announced in 2011.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Immigration ===\nFidesz has adopted anti-immigration stances and rhetoric.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2015/10/12/447911182/a-race-to-the-far-right-in-hungarian-politics|title=A Race to the Far Right in Hungarian Politics|publisher=NPR|access-date=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/hungary-eu-referendum-refugee-quota-migrant-crisis-xenophobia-border-control-racism-a7341276.html|title=Hungary set to reject EU refugee quotas in referendum|date=2 October 2016|work=The Independent|access-date=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/can-europe-make-it/annabel-tremlett/hungary's-future-antiimmigration-antimulticulturalism-and-antiro|title=Hungary's future: anti-immigration, anti-multiculturalism and anti-Roma?|date=3 August 2015|website=openDemocracy|access-date=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/02/hungary-government-condemned-over-anti-immigration-drive|title=Hungary government condemned over anti-immigration drive|last=Nolan|first=Daniel|date=2 July 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=28 February 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The Fidesz government has conversely began admitting increasing numbers of foreign workers due to a labour shortage resulting from strong economic growth, [[population decline]], and rising wages.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/hungary-loudly-opposed-to-immigration-opens-doors-to-more-foreign-workers-11567944008</ref><ref>https://hungarytoday.hu/immigration-foreigners-hungary-work-growing/</ref><ref>https://www.infomigrants.net/en/post/19841/in-orban-s-hungary-more-migrants-due-to-labor-shortage</ref>\n\n=== Nativism ===\nIn a 2018 address, Orb\u00e1n said \"We must state that we do not want to be diverse and do not want to be mixed: we do not want our own colour, traditions and national culture to be mixed with those of others. We do not want this. We do not want that at all. We do not want to be a diverse country.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.miniszterelnok.hu/prime-minister-viktor-orbans-speech-at-the-annual-general-meeting-of-the-association-of-cities-with-county-rights/|title=Prime Minister Viktor Orb\u00e1n's speech at the annual general meeting of the Association of Cities with County Rights \u2013 miniszterelnok.hu|website=miniszterelnok.hu|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Orb\u00e1n has \"often expressed a preference for a racially homogeneous society\".<ref name=\":5\"/> The Fidesz-led government has modified the country's Constitution to make it illegal to \"settle foreign populations in Hungary\".<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/20/world/europe/hungary-stop-soros-law.html|title=Hungary Criminalizes Aiding Illegal Immigrants|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=20 June 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nDespite a very low fertility rate that has led to a demographic deficit, the Fidesz government has remained steadfastly opposed to economic immigration that has been harnessed by other European countries to relieve its worker deficits. Instead, the government announced pecuniary incentives (including eliminating taxes for mothers with more than 3 children, and reducing credit payments and easier access to government-subsidized mortgages), and expanding day care and kindergarten access.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/11/world/europe/orban-hungary-babies-mothers-population-immigration.html|title=Orban Encourages Mothers in Hungary to Have 4 or More Babies|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=11 February 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Fidesz government's child incentive program also offers a 10-million-forint government-subsidized zero-interest loan to married couples who are willing to have a baby after 1 July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bank360.hu/en/blog/hungary-childbirth-incentive-program-2019|title=Hungary's new childbirth incentive program {{!}} Bank360|website=bank360.hu|language=hu|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Social policy ===\nChanges passed by the Fidesz government have given citizens the right to use arms for self-defense on one's own property.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/ruling-hungarian-fidesz-party-adopts-policies-of-far-right-jobbik-party-a-880590.html|title=Blurring Boundaries: Hungarian Leader Adopts Policies of Far-Right|last=Verseck|first=Keno|date=30 January 2013|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref> Fidesz has passed legislation [[Anti-homelessness legislation|criminalising homelessness]].<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/10/world/europe/hungary-orban-democracy-far-right.html|title=As West Fears the Rise of Autocrats, Hungary Shows What's Possible|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=10 February 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Christianity ====\nOrb\u00e1n has on multiple occasions emphasized upholding Christian values as central to his government,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/02/hungary-orban-vows-defence-christian-europe-190210195421238.html|title=Hungary's Orban vows defence of 'Christian' Europe|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/orban-christian-migrants-pledges-to-keep-hungary-safe/|title=Orb\u00e1n pledges to keep Hungary safe and Christian|last=Aleksandra Wr\u00f3bel|date=7 May 2018|work=Politico|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/hungary-general-election-viktor-orban-latest-christianity-nationalism-muslims-migrants-europe-racism-a8293836.html|title=Hungarian prime minister Viktor Orban vows to create 'Christian homeland' ahead of general election|date=7 April 2018|website=The Independent|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://profam.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Christmas-Speech-from-Viktor-Orban-2017-Prime-Minister-of-Hungary.pdf|title=We must defend Christian culture|last=Orban|first=Viktor}}</ref> and has described his government as creating a Christian democracy.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Other ===\n\n==== Anti-communism ====\nThe party is [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]].<ref name=\"yahoo\">\"[https://uk.finance.yahoo.com/news/eu-chief-defends-marx-controversial-speech-mark-communists-birth-173609688.html?guccounter=1 EU chief defends Marx in controversial speech to mark communist's birth]\". Yahoo News. 4 May 2018.</ref> In May 2018, the President of the [[European Commission]] [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] attended and spoke at a celebration of the deceased [[Karl Marx]]\u2019s 200th birthday, where he defended Marx's legacy. In response, MEPs from Fidesz wrote: \"Marxist ideology led to the death of tens of millions and ruined the lives of hundreds of millions. The celebration of its founder is a mockery of their memory.\"<ref name=\"yahoo\" />\n\nThe Fidesz government spokesman, Zolt\u00e1n Kov\u00e1cs, justified the government's controversial policies as an effort to \"get rid of the remnants of communism that are still with us, not only in terms of institutions but in terms of mentality.\"<ref name=\":34\" />\n\nDuring the party's rule, statues of communists regarded as traitors have been removed with Fidesz politicians in attendance, being replaced with statues of [[Mikl\u00f3s Horthy]].<ref name=\":13\" /> In December 2018, Hungarian authorities removed a statue of [[Imre Nagy]], a Hungarian reformist communist politician who led the failed anti-Soviet [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|1956 Hungarian Revolution]] and was later executed for his role in the uprising, to replace it with a memorial dedicated to the victims of the short-lived communist [[Hungarian Soviet Republic|1919 Hungarian Soviet Republic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46704111|title=Hungary removes uprising hero's statue|date=28 December 2018|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Direct democracy (National Consultations) and political informational campaigns ====\nThe government has often propagated Fidesz's political ideas in tax-funded advertisements, putting up posters portraying a grinning [[George Soros]] while calling on the citizens to oppose his purported support of illegal immigration (many of the posters portraying Soros \u2013 who is Jewish \u2013 were defaced with anti-Semitic graffiti),<ref name= \"Beauchamp\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/6/22/17493070/hungary-stop-soros-orban|title=Hungary just passed a 'Stop Soros' law that makes it illegal to help undocumented migrants|last= Beauchamp|first= Zack |date= 22 June 2018|website=Vox|access-date= 14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/11/08/hungary-accused-of-hatemongering-in-national-survey-targeting-george-soros|title=Hungary accused of 'hatemongering' in national survey targeting George Soros |last=Bearak|first=Max|website=The Washington Post}}</ref> posters depicting Soros and European Commission head [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] laughing together with text suggesting Soros' control of EU institutions (while also disseminating the accusation by letters sent to all Hungarian citizens),<ref name= \"Rankin\">{{Cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/19/brussels-orban-jean-claude-juncker-poster-george-soros-hungary|title=Brussels accuses Orb\u00e1n of peddling conspiracy theory with Juncker poster |last=Rankin|first= Jennifer |date=19 February 2019|work= The Guardian|access-date= 14 March 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url= https://www.politico.eu/article/commission-hits-back-over-hungarys-anti-juncker-campaign/ |title= Commission hits back over Hungary's anti-Juncker campaign|last=Bayer|first=Lili|date= 28 February 2019 |work=Politico |access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url= https://www.politico.eu/article/hungary-launches-campaign-targeting-jean-claude-juncker-george-soros/|title=Hungary launches campaign targeting Jean-Claude Juncker|last=Bayer|first=Lili|date= 18 February 2019|work=Politico |access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> and posters using the stock photo featuring photo models from the \"[[distracted boyfriend meme|distracted boyfriend]]\" internet meme to promote family values.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47557217|title='Distracted boyfriend' in pro-family ad|date=13 March 2019|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.politico.eu/article/hungary-uses-distracted-boyfriend-meme-couple-in-new-campaign-budapest-juncker-soros/ |title=Hungary uses 'distracted boyfriend' meme couple in new campaign |last=Dallison|first= Paul|date=13 March 2019|work= Politico |access-date= 14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe government has also employed so-called National Consultations, sending questionnaires to citizens that survey their opinions on government policy and legislation while pushing the Fidesz governments' ideology and agenda with suggestive questions (e.g. by referring to a supposed \"Soros plan\" to \"convince Brussels to resettle at least one million immigrants from Africa and the Middle East annually on the territory of the European Union, including Hungary\" and \"It is part of the Soros plan to launch political attacks on countries objecting to immigration and impose strict penalties on them\", and asking citizens whether they agree, or blasting \"Brussels bureaucrats\" in a consultation about family policy).<ref name=\":16\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|title=SAGE Journals |doi= 10.1177/0038038518762081}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.ft.com/content/76ce19e4-a768-11e7-93c5-648314d2c72c |title=Hungary steps up anti-Soros rhetoric with 'national consultation'}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://bbj.hu/politics/govt-launches-national-consultation-on-families-blasts-eu_157142 |title=Gov\u02bct launches 'National Consultation' on families, blasts EU|website= Budapest Business Journal |access-date= 14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Santora\" /> On other occasions \u2013 just prior to elections \u2013 the government sent letters notifying citizens that it will reduce their gas payments by \u20ac38, or sent pensioners gift vouchers.<ref name=\":25\" />\n\nThe Fidesz government has also carried out taxpayer-funded \"information campaigns\"/\"national messaging initiatives\" that have denounced supposed enemies of Hungary with budgets of tens of millions of euros per year.<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|url= https://www.politico.eu/article/viktor-orban-media-empire-hungary-election-antal-rogan-fidesz-propaganda/|title= Orb\u00e1n's media puppetmaster|date= 4 April 2018|work=Politico |access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Youth wing==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2016}}\nIn December 2005 the Congress of Fidesz established the Fidesz Youth Section (\"[[Fidelitas (Hungary)|Fidelitas]]\") as a division within the party gathering all members below the age of 30. The chairman of Fidesz Youth Section was D\u00e1niel Loppert until 2011. The current chairman is \u00c1ron Veress. The Fidesz Youth Section is member of European Democrat Students (EDS) and observer member in the Democrat Youth Community of Europe (DEMYC).\n\n== International affiliations ==\nFidesz is a member of the [[European People's Party]] (EPP) but was suspended on 20 March 2019.<ref name=\"Fid-EPP\" /> Prior to the [[2019 European Parliament election]], Fidesz announced it would discuss an alliance with Poland's [[Law and Justice]] (PiS) party if it leaves the EPP.<ref name=\"Hungary's Fidesz could consider alliance with Polish ruling party\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/viktor-orban-european-election-hungary-fidesz-could-consider-alliance-with-polish-ruling-party/|title=Orb\u00e1n: Hungary's Fidesz could consider alliance with Polish ruling party|last=Bayer|first=Lili|date=8 March 2019|work=Politico|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> The two nations' conservative governments have shared a close friendship and alliance for multiple years and the Polish government has pledged political support for Fidesz-led Hungary within the EU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/08/hungary-orban--fidesz-could-quit-epp-amid-anti-juncker-row|title=Hungary's Orb\u00e1n says Fidesz could quit EPP amid anti-Juncker row|last=Reuters|date=8 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=16 March 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2018/03/12/587949473/how-poland-and-hungary-are-forming-a-powerful-tag-team-against-brussels|title=How Poland And Hungary Are Forming A Powerful Tag Team Against Brussels|publisher=NPR|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-09-12/eu-lawmakers-poised-to-censure-hungary-as-allies-desert-orban|title=EU Votes on Hungary Censure Proposal as Allies Desert Orban}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/poland-and-hungarys-defiant-friendship-kaczynski-orban-pis-migration/|title=Poland and Hungary's defiant friendship|last=Chapman|first=Annabelle|date=6 January 2016|work=Politico|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref> Orb\u00e1n and PiS leader [[Jaros\u0142aw Kaczy\u0144ski]] have vowed to wage a \"cultural counter-revolution\" within the EU together,<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Financial Times]]|date=7 September 2016|title=Orban and Kaczynski vow \u2018cultural counter-revolution\u2019 to reform EU|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e825f7f4-74a3-11e6-bf48-b372cdb1043a}}</ref> with the Polish government seeing Hungary under Fidesz as a model for Poland.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Financial Times]]|title=Poland's new government finds a model in Orban's Hungary|date=6 January 2016|url=https://www.ft.com/content/0a3c7d44-b48e-11e5-8358-9a82b43f6b2f}}</ref>\n\nOrb\u00e1n and his government have gained favour with US president [[Donald Trump]] and his [[Republican Party (US)|Republican]] administration (in stark contrast to the policy of isolation practiced by the preceding [[Obama Admininstration]]).<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/new-economy-forum|title=EU's Populist Icon Orban Wins Trump's Attention in U.S. Reversal|website=Bloomberg}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/15/world/europe/hungary-us-orban-trump.html|title=Hungary's Leader Was Shunned by Obama, but Has a Friend in Trump|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=15 August 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Orb\u00e1n was the first European head of government to endorse Trump's presidential bid during the [[2016 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/trump-loves-a-strongman-so-of-course-he-fawns-over-hungarys-viktor-orban/2018/05/25/a10bff28-5f64-11e8-a4a4-c070ef53f315_story.html|title=Trump loves a strongman, so of course he fawns over Hungary's Viktor Orban|website=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/hungarys-viktor-orban-finds-ally-with-black-sheep-donald-trump/a-36520316|title=Hungary's Viktor Orban finds ally with 'black sheep' Donald Trump|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=25 November 2016|accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref> Trump has praised Hungary's anti-immigrant policies in a discussion with Orb\u00e1n.<ref name=\":11\" /> The more amiable attitude of the Trump Administration toward the Hungarian government prompted criticism and a protest by 22 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] lawmakers that called for a more disciplinary policy towards the country's government over what they perceived as a problematic track record.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/us-lawmakers-raise-concerns-about-president-donald-trump-administrations-hungary-policy-viktor-orban/|title=US lawmakers raise concerns about Trump administration's Hungary policy|date=10 October 2018|work=Politico|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> [[Steve Bannon]], former head of [[Breitbart News]] a former close associate of President Trump who had an integral role in Trump's electoral campaign and administration, has also praised Orb\u00e1n and announced plans to work with Fidesz in orchestrating the party's electoral campaign for the 2019 European parliament election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/09/world/europe/horowitz-europe-populism.html|title=Steve Bannon Is Done Wrecking the American Establishment. Now He Wants to Destroy Europe's.|last=Horowitz|first=Jason|date=9 March 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-orban-bannon-idUSKCN1NM07X|title=Ex-Trump strategist Bannon says to work with Hungary PM Orban: media|date=17 November 2018|agency=Reuters|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/steve-bannon-viktor-orban-hungary-budapest-european-parliament-elections-a8638591.html|title=Steve Bannon plans to advise Hungary's far right PM Viktor Orban|date=17 November 2018|website=The Independent|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/steve-bannon-praises-orban-and-salvini/|title=Steve Bannon praises Orb\u00e1n and Salvini|last=Dallison|first=Paul|date=16 September 2018|work=Politico|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />\n\nOrb\u00e1n has allied closely with former Slovenian PM [[Janez Jan\u0161a]] and the right-wing [[Slovenian Democratic Party]] he heads, going so far as to campaign for SDS during the [[2018 Slovenian parliamentary election]]. Businesspeople close to Orb\u00e1n also provided funds to SDS-affiliated media companies that then also used some of the funds to purchase campaign ads on behalf of SDS to circumvent Slovenian campaign finance laws.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/03/world/europe/slovenia-election.html|title=Slovenia Elections Tilt Another European Country to the Right|last=Surk|first=Barbara|date=3 June 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/04/world/europe/viktor-orban-media-slovenia.html|title=Safe in Hungary, Viktor Orban Pushes His Message Across Europe|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=4 June 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/185643/orb-n-ze-neposredno-financira-sds/|title=Orb\u00e1n \u017ee neposredno financira SDS|website=Mladina.si|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zurnal24.si/slovenija/madzarski-denar-za-financiranje-kampanje-sds-310541|title=Mad\u017earski denar za financiranje kampanje SDS?|website=zurnal24.si|language=hr|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref> After the election, and while SDS was struggling to secure political support to form a coalition government, Jan\u0161a again met with Orb\u00e1n on a private visit to Budapest; during the meeting, Orb\u00e1n also conducted a conference call with US president [[Donald Trump|Trump]] with Jan\u0161a joining in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042825976|title=Jan\u0161a na obisku pri Orbanu v Budimpe\u0161ti, opravili tudi konferen\u010dni klic s Trumpom|website=Dnevnik|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> SDS's unconditional backing of Fidesz within the EPP was reportedly pivotal in preventing Fidesz's expulsion from EPP, resulting in a more lenient suspension.<ref name=\":40\" /> In a letter to EPP leader, Jan\u0161a warned of an \"inevitable\" split in the EPP if the vote to expel Fidesz were to take place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/politics/news/exclusive-slovenian-center-right-cancel-orban-vote-or-epp-is-inevitably-split/|title=EXCLUSIVE-Slovenian centre-right: Cancel Orb\u00e1n vote or EPP is 'inevitably' split|last=Trkanjec|first=Zeljko|date=20 March 2019|website=euractiv.com|access-date=7 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOrb\u00e1n has also fostered close political ties with right-wing [[VMRO-DPMNE]] politician and former Macedonian PM [[Nikola Gruevski]]. While awaiting a ruling on an appeal to a corruption conviction in early 2019, Gruevski fled to Hungary to evade a looming jail sentence. The whereabouts of Gruevski were revealed only 4 days after he failed to report to serve his prison sentence. Macedonian officials have suggested that Gruevski (for whom an international arrest warrant had been issued) was in contact with Hungarian officials in the days preceding his flight, and Macedonian authorities have launched an investigation into whether Gruevski was transported across the border in a Hungarian diplomatic vehicle. The Hungarian government denied accusations of impropriety.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/29/world/europe/macedonia-hungary-orban-prime-minister.html|title=Hungary Sheltered a Fugitive Prime Minister. Did It Help Him Escape?|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=29 December 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Hungarian businesspeople close to Orb\u00e1n \u2013 the same that have previously invested into Slovenian right-wing media \u2013 have also entered into ownership of Macedonian right-wing media companies, propping up outlets friendly to Gruevski and his party.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOrb\u00e1n has a warm relationship with Serbian President [[Aleksandar Vu\u010di\u0107]] and his [[Serbian Progressive Party]], with the Hungarian Foreign Minister campaigning for Vu\u010di\u0107 before the [[2017 Serbian presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|work=Hungary Today|title=In Subotica, Serbia, PM Orb\u00e1n and Serbian President Vu\u010di\u0107 Praise Bilateral Ties|date=28 March 2018|url=https://hungarytoday.hu/inauguration-subotica-synagogue-viktor-orban-serbian-pm-aleksander-vucic-praise-bilateral-ties-56989/}}</ref> Companies close to the Orb\u00e1n government have won public contracts with the Serbian government.<ref>{{Cite web|work=Balkan Insight|title=Illumination of Serbia, Hungarian Style|date=26 June 2019|url=https://balkaninsight.com/2019/06/26/illumination-of-serbia-hungarian-style/}}</ref> The Serbian government has also been accused of taking a similar approach to the Hungarian government towards the media.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Newsweek]]|title=Viktor Orban's Authoritarian Media Control Is Spreading to Hungary's Neighbor, Report Warns|date=5 June 2019|url=https://www.newsweek.com/viktor-orbans-authoritarian-media-control-spreading-hungarys-neighbors-report-warns}}</ref>\n\nOrb\u00e1n and his government have also fostered close ties with the Israeli [[Likud]] government under [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], with the two heads of state forging a cordial relationship, having known one another for decades. Netanyahu advised Orb\u00e1n on economic reforms conducted by the Hungarian government in the early 2000s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.israelhayom.com/site/newsletter_article.php?id=44027|title=Hungarian PM: We share the same security concerns as Israel|newspaper=[[Israel Hayom]]|accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref> Netanyahu later extended public political support to Orb\u00e1n at a time when Orb\u00e1n was confronting criticism for praising [[Mikl\u00f3s Horthy]], Hungary's former leader, whose government passed anti-Jewish legislation and collaborated with Nazi Germany, and for allegedly employing anti-Semitic tropes in his criticism of [[George Soros]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/938bb193c0894691bf42a6457d1fae4c|title=Netanyahu greets Hungary's Orban as 'true friend of Israel'|last=Zion|first=Ilan Ben|date=19 July 2018|website=AP NEWS|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/netanyahu-orb-n-israel-welcome-hungary-prime-minister-antisemitism-a8454866.html|title=Israel's Netanyahu criticized for wooing Hungary's far-right PM|date=19 July 2018|website=The Independent|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/posteverything/wp/2018/07/13/anti-semitism-doesnt-bother-benjamin-netanyahu-if-it-comes-from-his-political-allies/|title=Anti-Semitism doesn't bother Benjamin Netanyahu if it comes from his political allies|website=The Washington Post}}</ref> The Israeli foreign ministry issued a statement condemning Soros in a show of solidarity with the Orb\u00e1n government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-hungary-soros-idUSKBN19V1J4|title=Israel backs Hungary, says financier Soros is a threat|date=11 July 2017|agency=Reuters|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/07/world/europe/hungary-viktor-orban-election.html|title=Orban Campaigns on Fear, With Hungary's Democracy at Stake|first=Marc|last=Santora|date=7 April 2018|work=The New York Times}}</ref> A Likud lawmaker also introduced legislation modeled on Fidesz's \"Stop Soros law\" in the Israeli [[Knesset]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/amid-hungary-s-anti-soros-moves-israeli-lawmaker-pushes-his-own-soros-law-1.5492942|title=With Hungary Cracking Down on Soros, Israeli Lawmaker Pushes His Own 'Soros Law'|date=11 July 2017|work=Haaretz|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOrb\u00e1n expressed strong support for [[Tomislav Karamarko]]'s leadership of the [[Croatian Democratic Union]] (HDZ), having written a letter endorsing Karamarko for his stance on immigration that was read out at an HDZ rally during the [[2015 Croatian parliamentary election]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Politico]]|date=11 July 2015|title=Croatian election hinges on migration and the economy|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/croatia-election-migrants-asylum-borders-election/}}</ref>\n\nOrb\u00e1n has more recently cultivated close ties between Fidesz and the [[Freedom Party of Austria]] (FP\u00d6), noting \"strategic cooperation\" between the parties and \"friendly ties based on mutual confidence and Christian-conservative values\".<ref>https://hungarytoday.hu/orban-fidesz-fpo-hofer-cooperation/</ref> Prior to the [[2019 Austrian legislative election]], he held a joint press conference with FP\u00d6 leader [[Norbert Hofer]], where he wished the party success in the upcoming election and stressed the \"similar views\" of the two parties.<ref>https://www.kormany.hu/en/the-prime-minister/news/prime-minister-viktor-orban-hopes-that-austria-will-have-a-strong-and-stable-government-that-rejects-political-islam</ref>\n\nOrb\u00e1n has praised the tenure of former Italian Interior Minister [[Matteo Salvini]], the leader of the [[Lega Nord|League]], declaring him an \"ally and our fellow combatant in the fight for the preservation of European Christian heritage and the tackling of migration\" after Salvini's departure from the Italian government in August 2019.<ref>https://www.euractiv.com/section/elections/news/orban-commiserates-with-fellow-combatant-salvini/</ref> Orb\u00e1n previously urged closer political ties between the EPP and the League,<ref>https://www.euractiv.com/section/eu-elections-2019/news/orban-says-salvini-is-the-most-important-politician-in-europe/</ref> and cooperated extensively on immigration with Salvini, describing Salvini as \"my hero\".<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/28/matteo-salvini-viktor-orban-anti-migrant-plan-brussels</ref>\n\nOrb\u00e1n sent a letter of support to [[V\u00e1clav Klaus Jr.]]'s newly formed [[Tricolour Citizens' Movement]] in the Czech Republic.<ref>https://www.novinky.cz/domaci/clanek/trikolora-zahajila-snem-mazoretkami-klaus-zatim-nema-vyzyvatele-40298032</ref> Orb\u00e1n has a relationship with Klaus's father, President [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], who has expressed support for Orb\u00e1n's rule.<ref>https://hungarytoday.hu/vaclav-klaus-europe-need-organized-migration-98522/</ref>\n\nOrb\u00e1n has also developed ties with Dutch [[Party for Freedom]] (PVV) leader [[Geert Wilders]],<ref>https://zoom.hu/hir/2018/02/19/valojaban-orban-viktor-hivta-meg-geert-wilderst-ebedelni-januarban/</ref> [[Brothers of Italy]] leader [[Giorgia Meloni]],<ref>https://www.repubblica.it/speciali/politica/elezioni2018/2018/02/28/foto/meloni_sceglie_il_gruppo_di_visegrad_a_budapest_la_foto_con_orban-189990321/1/</ref> and [[Estonian Conservative People's Party]] leader [[Mart Helme]].<ref>https://news.err.ee/967871/mart-helme-lauds-cooperation-with-hungarian-prime-minister</ref> However, he has rejected association with [[Marine Le Pen]]'s [[National Rally (France)|National Rally]],<ref>https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/link-italys-salvini-hungarys-orban-downplayed-63372890</ref> and instead endorsed [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]], the candidate of [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]], in the [[2017 French presidential election]].<ref>https://apnews.com/71de471223cc486cac44f6c70e448133/Hungary's-Orban-praises-Trump's-'end-of-multilateralism' </ref>\n\n== Criticism and controversies ==\n\n=== Authoritarianism ===\nThe Fidesz government has been accused of \"[chipping] away at the country's democratic framework, reducing judicial independence, taking control of most state and private media and reshaping the electoral system to favor [...] Fidesz.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/17/world/europe/hungary-lawmakers-assaulted.html|title=4 Lawmakers Assaulted in Hungary, as Protests Against Orban Continue|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=17 December 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 March 2019|last2=Novak|first2=Benjamin|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It has also been accused of providing a \"blueprint for the erosion of democratic institutions\" in countries like Poland, Italy, France, the Netherlands, and Brazil, while leaving analysts struggling to determine \"whether Hungary is still a democracy\".<ref name=\":5\"/><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/16/world/europe/hungary-protests-viktor-orban.html|title=Opposition in Hungary Demonstrates Against Orban, in Rare Display of Dissent|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=16 December 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Bertelsmann Stiftung]], a German research organisation, has assessed that Hungary under Fidesz-led government is approaching [[autocracy]].<ref name=\":32\"/> Fidesz's governance has been described by some as reminiscent of communist-led Hungary of the [[J\u00e1nos K\u00e1d\u00e1r|K\u00e1d\u00e1r]]-era.<ref name=\":25\" />\n\nThe Fidesz government appointed former party politicians to non-partisan oversight institutions that were created as checks on government power after the fall of the communist regime. The institutions involved included the State Audit Office, the State Prosecution Service, and the National Fiscal Council.<ref name=\":34\"/><ref name=\":35\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/22/world/europe/foes-of-hungarys-government-fear-demolition-of-democracy.html|title=Foes of Hungary's Government Fear \u2018Demolition of Democracy\u2019|last=Kulish|first=Nicholas|date=21 December 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/768453/hungarys-illiberal-democracy|title=Hungary's 'illiberal democracy'|date=22 April 2018|website=theweek.com|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the government proposed legislation that could endanger the independence of the Hungarian central bank, according to the then head of the organisation, Andr\u00e1s Simor. The law was also criticized by [[European Central Bank]] president [[Mario Draghi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/16/world/europe/hungary-moves-against-its-central-bank.html|title=Hungarian Bill Could Take Power From Central Bank|last=Kulish|first=Nicholas|date=15 December 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Due to the controversial central bank reforms, IMF and European Commission representatives walked away from 2011 negotiations about providing assistance for the heavily indebted Hungary.<ref name=\":35\" /> A Fidesz loyalist was later appointed to head the central bank.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/11/world/europe/viktor-orban-european-peoples-party.html|title=E.U.\u2019s Leadership Seeks to Contain Hungary's Orban|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=11 September 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nTaking power in 2010 with a supermajority able to propose and pass legislation largely at will, Fidesz has often denied parliament sufficient time to deliberate proposals, sometimes giving only a few hours' notice before discussions on proposals and only allowing a few hours of debate.<ref name=\":35\" /><ref name=\":34\" /> The laws were also often presented by low-ranking lawmakers that had neither written nor read the legislation they were introducing.<ref name=\":34\" />\n\nMembers of Fidesz have argued that the party is simply pursuing an alternative model of democracy, different from the common example of [[liberal democracy]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/25/world/europe/hungary-democracy-orban.html|title=On the Surface, Hungary Is a Democracy. But What Lies Underneath?|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=25 December 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Press freedom ====\nThe Fidesz government has been accused of \"silencing media\"<ref name=\":4\"/> and controlling all major media outlets in Hungary,<ref name=\":2\" /> thus creating an echo chamber that has excluded alternative political voices.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/29/world/europe/hungary-orban-media.html|title=Orban and His Allies Cement Control of Hungary's News Media|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=29 November 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":8\" /> The government has been accused of selectively starving non-loyal media organisations of government advertising revenues (the government is the country's second largest advertizer<ref name=\":28\" />) while pressuring the owners by targeting their other business interests so that the owners would either fall in line or sell their media holdings. Over 500 Hungarian news outlets were said to be supportive of the government in their coverage as of 2018, up from only 31 in 2015.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> By 2017, 90% of all Hungarian media was owned by either the state or by Fidesz allies, according to one Hungarian scholar.<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> All regional newspapers are said to be controlled by pro-Fidesz owners.<ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />\n\nOrb\u00e1n attributed Fidesz's 2002 electoral loss to the country's \"liberal media\", initiating a campaign to recruit loyalists who would buy up media outlets and create a more friendly media environment while engaging operatives to coordinate and administer the media under the government's sway.<ref name=\":28\" /><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> Media organisations owned by Fidesz-friendly oligarchs are said to coordinate daily press coverage, following \"preset news themes\".<ref name=\":28\" />\n\nShortly after taking power in 2010, Orb\u00e1n passed laws enabling him to appoint candidates to lead the country's main media regulators while expanding the powers of the same regulators to fine and punish media organisations.<ref name=\":34\"/> The law would also impose hefty fines for coverage it finds \"unbalanced or offensive to human dignity or common morals\". The law was strongly condemned by the European community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/26/world/europe/26hungary.html|title=Hungary Waves Off Criticism Over Media Law|last=Dempsey|first=Judy|date=25 December 2010|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Journalists working for public media organisations are furthermore required by law to \"promote a national identity\" in their reporting.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nState media is said to be \"entirely loyal to\" Orb\u00e1n and his government, and has been accused of refusing to cover protests opposing the government.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/18/world/europe/hungary-protest-orban.html|title=Outside Hungary's State Television: A Protest. On Air: Pigeon Talk.|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=18 December 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":26\" /> Soon after taking power, the Fidesz government dispatched new managers to the offices of the Hungarian public radio that were later characterized as \"propagandists\" by an employee (a popular radio host). A third of the staff at public broadcasters was also purged.<ref name=\":34\"/>\n\nJournalist require government permits to report from near the national border.<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} The government has been accused of blocking journalists' access to refugee camps and immigrant transit centres, restricting refugee-related coverage, and government forces have been accused of forcing journalists to delete footage, physically attacking journalists, and damaging journalists' equipment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ifex.org/hungary/2015/09/23/censored_attacked/|title=Journalists covering refugee crisis censored, attacked by Hungarian authorities|website=IFEX|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nPro-government media has been known to attack and deride opposition politicians and other critics, including a high school student that criticized and lampooned the government and Fidesz politicians during a protest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jan/21/hungary-pithy-insult-dogs-orban-as-anti-government-protesters-resort-to-ridicule|title=Hungary: pithy insults fly as anti-Orb\u00e1n protesters resort to ridicule|last=Walker|first=Shaun|date=21 January 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=16 March 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />\n\nThe independent opposition-aligned radio station Klubr\u00e1dio was taken off air by the Hungary's media council in 2011.<ref name=\":35\" /> The largest-circulation daily newspaper, [[N\u00e9pszabads\u00e1g]], was shut down shortly after publishing a story about a profligate luxury helicopter trip of close Fidesz ally and media operative Antal Rog\u00e1n and his family.<ref name=\":28\" /> In 2018, immediately following a landslide Fidesz electoral victory, [[Magyar Nemzet]], one of the two national daily newspapers opposed to the government (which had been in print for 80 years) and its sister radio station (both owned by Lajos Simicska, a businessman that entered into confrontation with Orb\u00e1n in 2015 after a longstanding alliance between the two) announced their intention to cease operations due in part to a government advertising boycott.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-election-media-idUSKBN1HH10S|title=Major Hungarian opposition newspaper to close after Orban victory|date=11 April 2018|agency=Reuters|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/hungary-opposition-newspaper-magyar-nemzet-to-shut/|title=Hungarian opposition newspaper to close|last=Schlee|first=Maxime|date=10 April 2018|work=Politico|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> H\u00edr TV, another media holding of Simicska's media empire, was converted into a pro-government outlet.<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />\n\nThe transformation of Origo, Hungary's leading news website, from an opposition publication to a government-friendly one has been regarded as an exemplary \"cautionary tale\" for the stifling of press independence. The site was established in the late 1990s by Magyar Telekom and gradually evolved its investigative journalistic brand. In 2013, Origo wast Hungary's most-read news website known for its investigative journalism. Magyar Telekom was acquired by the German [[Deutsche Telekom]] (DT) in 2005. In 2010, DT encountered a hostile business environment fostered by the new Fidesz government which adopted punitive measures against foreign owners of domestic companies. During DT's negotiations with the Hungarian government over telecommunications policy, a senior Fidesz official (J\u00e1nos L\u00e1z\u00e1r) suggested a covert line of communication between the government and Origo editors because \"Origo's journalists had historically struggled to grasp the government's perspective on certain matters\". Origo signed a contract with a media consultancy firm run by Attila V\u00e1rhegyi, a former senior Fidesz member, after which the telecommunications deal was finailized on terms favourable to DT. This resulted in a revolt of Origo employees and editors. During the first half of 2014, political interference in journalists' work and editorial policy began to become noticeable, according to one former employee. After one Origo journalist launched an investigation of L\u00e1z\u00e1r's foreign travel expenses despite V\u00e1rhegyi's firm's requests to slow the investigation, L\u00e1z\u00e1r complained to Magyar Telekom executives in 2014. Origo, headed by a combative editor-in-chief (Gerg\u0151 S\u00e1ling) protecting a tenacious investigative reporter, persisted in scrutinising L\u00e1z\u00e1r's record and eventually launched court proceedings to obtain documents regarding L\u00e1z\u00e1r while also publishing several pieces unfavourable to L\u00e1z\u00e1r. After Orb\u00e1n re-election and months of pressure, Magyar Telekom gave in and fired the editor shielding the investigations. Several journalists resigned in protest. Regarding it as a political liability, Magyar Telekom decided to sell Origo. In an open sale process, businesspeople close to the ruling party purchased the news outlet. By 2018, Origo's coverage took a steadfastly pro-government stance.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/24/world/europe/hungary-viktor-orban-media.html|title=The Website That Shows How a Free Press Can Die|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=24 November 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|last2=Novak|first2=Benjamin|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2019-02-12/orb-n-rises-hungarys-free-press-falls|title=As Orb\u00e1n rises, Hungary's free press falls|website=Public Radio International|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2018, over 400 news media outlets \u2013 most of the private media in the country \u2013 were consolidated into a central holding company, the [[Central European Press and Media Foundation]], administered by people close to the government. The media organisations were transferred to the Foundation by over a dozen pro-government business \"moguls\" and were already highly supportive of the government. The move was thus largely symbolic, but nonetheless unprecedented within the EU. One of the foundation's board members announced the Foundation has an \"undeniably\" right-wing agenda and that one of its goals is to prevent \"opposition-minded media outlets\" from regaining \"the prominent market position that they held before Mr. Orban's election\".<ref name=\":7\" /> Viktor Orb\u00e1n argued that in Hungary still the \"leftist, liberal media outlets are in majority\", and the new foundation created became a national interest because it is non-profit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://index.hu/belfold/2019/01/10/orban_viktor_sajtotajekoztato_osszefoglalo/|title=Orb\u00e1n: A mai napon is ellensz\u00e9lben fogok dolgozni|first=Dull Szabolcs, Rov\u00f3|last=Attila|date=10 January 2019|website=index.hu}}</ref>\n\n===== Slovenia-Hungary diplomatic row over press freedom =====\nOn 22 March 2019, Slovenian weekly political magazine ''[[Mladina]]'' published an issue with the feature article detailing the intervention of the [[Slovenian Democratic Party]] within the [[European People's Party]] (of which SDS is a member) to prevent Fidesz's exclusion from EPP, reporting that SDS was the pivotal factor in EPP's decision to enact the much more lenient suspension of Fidesz's membership instead of a full ousting. The issue also featured a comical cartoon cover portraying Hungarian MP Orb\u00e1n giving a [[Nazi salute]]<ref name=\":40\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/190431/hungary-s-attempt-to-control-slovenian-media/|title=Hungary's attempt to control Slovenian media|website=Mladina.si|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"mladina.si\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/190334/predstavnik-madzarske-vlade-o-mladini-primerjave-med-orb-nom-in-nacizmom-so-nesprejemljive/|title=Predstavnik mad\u017earske vlade o Mladini: Primerjave med Orb\u00e1nom in nacizmom so nesprejemljive|website=Mladina.si|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref> and wearing a Hungarian flag armband while being amorously embraced by SDS politicians (with one of them holding a Slovenian flag featuring the Hungarian tricolor).<ref name=\":40\" /><ref name=\":41\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/slovenia-dismisses-hungary-embassy-protest-of-orban-cartoon/2019/04/05/c9c9d0f6-57ad-11e9-aa83-504f086bf5d6_story.html|title=Slovenia dismisses Hungary embassy protest of Orban cartoon}}</ref> ''Mladina''<nowiki/>'s cover was widely covered by Hungarian opposition media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/190216/mladinina-naslovnica-je-hit-na-madzarskem/|title=Mladinina naslovnica je hit na Mad\u017earskem|website=Mladina.si|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref> ''Mladina'' has long been known for its satirical and politically provocative covers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtvslo.si/news-in-english/slovenia-revealed/a-slovenian-poster-challenged-yugoslavia-s-communist-orthodoxy/326571|title=A Slovenian poster challenged Yugoslavia's Communist orthodoxy|website=RTVSLO.si|language=sl|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tol.org/client/article/22611-how-a-slovenian-magazine-found-yugoslavias-weak-spot.html|title=How a Slovenian Magazine Found Yugoslavia's Weak Spot \u2013 Transitions Online|website=tol.org|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mg-lj.si/en/exhibitions/2026/exhibition-mladina-magazine/|title=EXHIBITION {{!}} Mladina 1980s \u2013 MG+MSUM|website=www.mg-lj.si|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KcKAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=mladina+provocative+cover+slovenian+yugoslavia#v=onepage&q=mladina%20provocative%20cover%20slovenian%20yugoslavia&f=false|title=Slovenia: Evolving Loyalties|last=Cox|first=John K.|date=June 2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134478989}}</ref>\n\nThe portrayal of Orb\u00e1n was harshly criticised by Hungary's ambassador to Slovenia, and by the Hungarian press secretary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/190238/odziv-madzarske-veleposlanice-na-mladinino-porocanje-o-demokraciji-na-madzarskem/|title=Odziv mad\u017earske veleposlanice na Mladinino poro\u010danje o demokraciji na Mad\u017earskem|website=Mladina.si|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"mladina.si\"/> The ambassador's protest was lampooned by the magazine, which published a \"corrected and courteous\" cover, now portraying Orb\u00e1n, with a flower in his hair, extending an olive branch,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/190299/popravljena-in-prijazna-naslovnica/|title=Popravljena in prijazna naslovnica|website=Mladina.si|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref> while ''Mladina''<nowiki/>'s cartoonist jestingly published a sarcastic \"apology\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/190362/opravicilo/|title=Opravi\u010dilo|website=Mladina.si|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, the Slovenian Foreign Ministry dismissed a formal request by the Hungarian embassy on the topic of the contentious ''Mladina'' cover that called on Slovene authorities to assist the Hungarian government in preventing \"similar incidents\" from occurring in the future because \"the Hungarian embassy in Ljubljana is convinced that actions such as the publication of the aforementioned cover harm the otherwise excellent bilateral cooperation between the countries\".<ref name=\":41\" /><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/hungary-slovenia-viktor-orban-censorship-request/|title=Hungary and Slovenia in diplomatic row over censorship request|last=Bayer|first=Lili|date=5 April 2019|work=Politico|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sta.si/2623712/madzarska-z-diplomatsko-noto-nad-mladinino-naslovnico|title=STA: Mad\u017earska z diplomatsko noto nad Mladinino naslovnico|website=sta.si|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mladina.si/190409/madzarska-je-od-slovenskega-zunanjega-ministrstva-zahtevala-pomoc-pri-sankcioniranju-mladine/|title=Mad\u017earska je od slovenskega zunanjega ministrstva zahtevala pomo\u010d pri sankcioniranju Mladine|website=Mladina.si|access-date=13 April 2019}}</ref> The Ministry responded by stating \"[we] strictly respect the freedom of speech and freedom of the press and would never interfere in any of the media's editorial policy\".<ref name=\":42\" /> The request was condemned by the Slovenian Journalists' Association,<ref name=\":41\" /> multiple MPs of Slovenia's governing coalition, the president, prime minister, and other prominent politicians, with one MP announcing that he will be requesting that the parliamentary Committee on Culture and Foreign Policy be convened over the issue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siol.net/novice/slovenija/dns-madzarska-diplomatska-nota-glede-mladinine-naslovnice-dokaz-resnosti-razmer-v-evropi-494523|title=DNS: Mad\u017earska diplomatska nota zaradi Mladinine naslovnice dokaz resnosti razmer v Evropi|website=siol.net|language=sl|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":43\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnevnik.si/1042882292|title=Mad\u017earska protestirala pri slovenskem zunanjem ministrstvu zaradi Mladinine naslovnice|website=Dnevnik|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":44\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.delo.si/novice/slovenija/repovz-nota-madzarske-ambasadorke-nam-kaze-s-kom-ima-opravka-slovenska-drzava-168511.html|title=FOTO:Repov\u017e: Nota mad\u017earske ambasadorke nam ka\u017ee, s kom ima opraviti slovenska dr\u017eava|last=STA|first=Suzana Kos, L. Z., V. U.|date=5 April 2019|website=delo.si|language=sl-si|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref> Multiple diplomats and experts also expressed consternation over what they described as an unprecedented/\"unheard of\" diplomatic move.<ref name=\":43\" /><ref name=\":44\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24ur.com/novice/slovenija/madzarska-protestirala-pri-slovenskem-zunanjem-ministrstvu-zaradi-mladinine-naslovnice.html|title=Ne spomnim se, da bi se to \u017ee kdaj zgodilo v EU|website=24ur.com|language=sl|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of the judiciary ====\nThe Fidesz government has been accused of removing independent judges,<ref name=\":4\"/> stacking the Constitutional Court and judicial institutions with loyalists,<ref name=\":7\"/> and appointing as chief prosecutor a former party member who has seldom pursued corruption charges against Fidesz politicians.<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/02/world/europe/hungary-judges-independence.html|title=Hungary's Judges Warn of Threats to Judicial Independence|last=Novak|first=Benjamin|date=2 May 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|last2=Kingsley|first2=Patrick|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the government lowered the mandatory retirement age from 70 to 62, forcing judges to retire and freeing up vacancies for appointments by the government.<ref name=\":35\" /> In 2012, the government was criticized by the [[Venice Commission]] for concentrating too much power in a single official, the head of the then recently established National Judicial Office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/22/world/europe/hungary-is-pressed-to-change-its-laws-further.html|title=Hungary Pressed to Alter Laws on Judiciary and News Media|last=Karasz|first=Palko|date=21 March 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|last2=Eddy|first2=Melissa|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nFidesz dismantled a Constitution Court nominations committee that was originally staffed by representatives of all parliamentary parties to ensure consensus, instead taking complete control over the nomination process.<ref name=\":34\"/> The size of the Constitutional Court was expanded to allow for stacking by Fidesz appointees.<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> This resulted in all Constitutional Court judges being appointees of Fidesz after 8 years of its rule, with multiple judges having close connections to the party and the Constitutional Court consistently voting in line with the Fidesz government. In instances where laws were struck down by the Court as unconstitutional, the Fidesz-dominated parliament simply amended to Constitution.<ref name=\":34\" /> The authority of the Constitutional Court was also constricted by the new Constitution in 2011 in a move that further drained power away from the judicial branch.<ref name=\":35\" />\n\nIn 2018, T\u00fcnde Hand\u00f3, the government's judicial chief with close personal ties to Orb\u00e1n and Fidesz, was accused by an independent panel of senior judges of abusing her function to interfere with the appointment process for senior judges in a move that confirmed longstanding accusations by individual judges and the political opposition. Hando unsuccessfully attempted to prevent the council from convening to frustrate the release of the report.<ref name=\":29\" /> A flurry of judges' resignations prior to the report's release had also fueled suspicions that \"something [...] sinister was afoot\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/01/world/europe/hungary-viktor-orban-judges.html|title=After Viktor Orban's Victory, Hungary's Judges Start to Tumble|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=1 May 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe Fidesz-dominated parliament has altered the Constitution to establish a \"parallel court system\" to handle cases pertaining to public administration, leading to fears that the new courts would be stacked by government loyalists and used to approve contentious politically motivated reforms and actions (\"for instance dismissing challenges to government decisions, penalizing civil servants whose loyalty to Mr. Orb\u00e1n is in doubt or rejecting freedom of information requests from journalists investigating government corruption\").<ref name=\":27\" /><ref name=\":30\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/12/world/europe/hungary-courts.html|title=Hungary Creates New Court System, Cementing Leader's Control of Judiciary|last=Novak|first=Benjamin|date=12 December 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|last2=Kingsley|first2=Patrick|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The government has argued that the new judicial system is in keeping with European and international norms and recommendations, and that the system will be independent and more efficient.<ref name=\":30\" />\n\n==== Electoral reform ====\nThe Fidesz-led government has redrawn electoral boundaries in a move that critics have condemned as [[Gerrymandering|favouring the party]].<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":26\" /> The Fidesz government has also abolished the two-round/round-off election system, strengthening its preeminent position while further confounding and weakening the fragmented opposition.<ref name=\":26\" /> The electoral system has also been reformed in a way that gives advantage to parties that won more constituencies which has so far also benefited Fidesz.<ref name=\":34\"/> Fidesz has also passed legislation setting up lax requirements and financial incentives for creating new political parties. The resulting proliferation of \"bogus parties\" has further divided the opposition vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.occrp.org/en/37-ccblog/ccblog/9019-fake-parties-real-money-hungary-s-bogus-party-problem|title=Fake Parties, Real Money: Hungary's Bogus Party Problem|last=Cooper|first=Alex|website=occrp.org|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/04/04/bogus-political-parties-are-swindling-hungary-out-of-millions-of-euros-|title=Never mind fake news, the Hungarian election has a fake party problem|last=Harris|first=Chris|date=4 April 2018|website=euronews|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hungarianspectrum.org/2018/03/11/fidesz-created-bogus-parties-as-means-of-political-gain/|title=Fidesz-created bogus parties as means of political gain|last=Balogh|first=Eva S.|date=11 March 2018|website=Hungarian Spectrum|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref> Fidesz candidates have also been accused of directly colluding with the \"bogus parties\" to prop them up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hungarianspectrum.org/2018/03/20/collusion-fidesz-and-the-bogus-parties/|title=Collusion: Fidesz and the bogus parties|last=Balogh|first=Eva S.|date=20 March 2018|website=Hungarian Spectrum|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> By expanding the ability to easily gain citizenship to ethnic Hungarians abroad with a 2010 [[Hungarian nationality law|law]], Fidesz was able to greatly expand its electorate; about 10% of the current electorate acquired voting rights due to the measure, with 95% of these voting Fidesz.<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> The government has also been accused of blocking opposition candidates from publishing ads in state media while allowing the same for Fidesz candidates.<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />\n\nThe [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]], an international election observer, has accused Fidesz of using government resources to bolster its electoral chances, \"[blurring] the line between state and party\" during the 2018 parliamentary election. It also reported \"media bias, and opaque campaign financing\", describing the election as \"free but not entirely fair\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/09/world/europe/hungary-election-orban-fidesz.html|title=Hungary Election Was Free but Not Entirely Fair, Observers Say|last=Santora|first=Marc|date=9 April 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=16 March 2019|last2=Bienvenu|first2=Helene|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/osce-observers-raise-concerns-over-hungary-election-viktor-orban-fidesz/|title=International observers raise concerns over Hungary election|last=Bayer|first=Lili|date=9 April 2018|work=Politico|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Civil society ====\nThe Orb\u00e1n government has been accused of infringing on a free civil society.<ref name=\":11\" /> The Fidesz-led Hungarian government passed a bill allegedly targeting the Soros-funded [[Central European University]]; the bill would effectively prevent CEU's operation. The law was denounced both domestically and internationally as it was perceived as infringing upon academic freedom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/hungary-ceu-story/|title=Hungary passes bill targeting Soros-funded university|last=Bayer|first=Lili|date=4 April 2017|work=Politico|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":38\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/03/world/europe/soros-hungary-central-european-university.html|title=George Soros-Founded University Is Forced Out of Hungary|last=Santora|first=Marc|date=3 December 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=17 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> CEU announced it was closing down due to government pressure in December 2018.<ref name=\":38\" />\n\nThe Hungarian government has cracked down on NGOs that receive foreign donations; such organisations have to register with authorities and follow stringent rules to declare their foreign funding (including on all websites and publications) or risk fines or termination.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2017/06/hungarys-anti-foreign-ngo-law/530121/|title=Hungary's Anti-Foreign NGO Law|last=Serhan|first=Yasmeen|date=13 June 2017|website=The Atlantic|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fidh.org/en/issues/human-rights-defenders/hungary-new-bill-hampers-ngos-access-to-funding-and-seriously|title=HUNGARY: New bill hampers NGOs' access to funding and seriously threatens civil society|website=Worldwide Movement for Human Rights|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/hungary-approves-anti-foreign-ngo-law/|title=Hungary approves anti-foreign NGO law|last=Saeed|first=Saim|date=13 June 2017|work=Politico|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":22\"/><ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/beyond-brussels/140990|title=Hungary plans to paralyse NGOs dealing with migration|website=EUobserver|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> In 2018, the government also passed laws (the \"Stop Soros Law\") that financially sanction any NGO that \"promotes illegal migration\",<ref name=\":15\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/viktor-orbans-campaign-against-george-soros-mercenaries/a-44954661|title=Viktor Orban's campaign against George Soros 'mercenaries'|last=Verseck|first=Keno|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=4 August 2018|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-orban-ngos-idUSKBN1HW1ZN|title=Civil organizations in Hungary brace for government crackdown on NGOs|date=25 April 2018|agency=Reuters|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> threaten activists that organize or support migration or carry out work contrary to \"Hungary's national security interests\" with restraining orders preventing them from approaching the boarder,<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":23\" /> criminalize assistance to asylum seekers (\"facilitating illegal immigration\") thus potentially threatening activists, lawyers, and NGO employees with prison sentences,<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44546030|title=Help for migrants outlawed in Hungary|date=20 June 2018|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> allow the banishing of foreign citizens who support migration from the country, and vest the interior minister with the authority to review organisations involved in immigration advocacy and forbid them if they are deemed to represent a \"national security risk\".<ref name=\":23\" /> The reform has been widely condemned, including by the UN, and Amnesty International.<ref name=\":27\" />\n\nIn 2018, the youth wing of Fidesz engaged in a campaign marking the buildings of civil organisations with red stickers with the message \"This organization supports immigration\".<ref name=\":15\"/>\n\nFidesz's attacks on civil society organisations are often combined with attacks on Hungarian-born financier [[George Soros]] whom they accuse of attempting to undermine the traditional Hungarian and European societal values by surreptitiously and insidiously promoting mass migration through covert channels that include NGOs.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":22\"/><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":15\"/><ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> After 35 years, Soros' [[Open Society Foundations]] relocated from Budapest to Berlin in 2018 due to the increasingly hostile attitude the government has taken against the organisation and its founder.<ref name=\":15\"/>\n\nThe government's crackdown on civil society organisations has been criticized as an assault on the only bastion of democratic checks and balances and opposition to the Fidesz government and its agenda.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":14\"/>\n\nThe National Cooperation Fund, headed by L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Csizmadia, a vocal Fidesz supporter, has preferentially tended to support groups with religious and nationalist aims, with three of the top recipient organisations led by Fidesz politicians. Csizmadia, a right-wing theorist, has on numerous occasions written about his belief that the function of NGOs should be to \"preserve national identity and uphold Christian values\" and that civil society should be subjugated to the will of the government to enact the will of the people.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/27/world/europe/viktor-orban-hungary.html|title=How Viktor Orban Bends Hungarian Society to His Will|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=27 March 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe government funding squeeze of non-loyal NGOs has left these starved of resources; NGOs have thus increasingly turned to foreign donors to finance their operations, in particular, the Norwegian government, and the Soros-headed Open Society Foundation. The government had subsequently raided some organisations distributing Norwegian funds while accusing recipients of being beholden to foreign powers. In a meeting with a government minister, PM Orb\u00e1n reportedly labelled NGOs as \"foreign-funded enemies of the state\" that he wished to eliminate completely.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\nThe government has battled educators over textbook content that promotes a narrative of ethnocentrism and Hungarian victimhood. The government line has been pushed into school textbooks; history textbooks present Orb\u00e1n's views on the threat of immigration, going on to state that \"It can be problematic for different cultures to coexist\", and the high school curriculum has been expanded to include teaching the new Fidesz-passed Hungarian Constitution (that includes provisions that may discriminate against religious minorities). Funding of university departments has been transferred to government-appointed supervisors in a move the government argues was intended to reduce costs.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\nFidesz appointees and loyalists have also come to dominate artistic institutions and universities. Art exhibitions and plays have begun to assume nationalist and anti-Western undertones. The government wields the authority to appoint theatre directors, and it has, in one instance, appointed a director who pledged to promote Hungarian values and combat liberalism, and attract audiences that believe in a \"nation state\", while in another instance summoning a theatre director that was appointed by the previous government and produced plays that questioned \"Hungarian national narratives\" for questioning by Parliament and later refusing to renew his contract. The government also recruited a group of right-wing artists with ties to Fidesz and turned it into a government agency with the power to distribute stipends and prizes to artists that displayed a \"clear national commitment\".<ref name=\":32\" />\n\n\"The government is using its democratic legitimacy not only to reform the state but to reform the society\" said professor Andras Patyi who had headed a new university established by Fidesz to train future civil servants, police, and soldiers, adding that other leaders in democratic societies have commonly attempted to do the same.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\nReligious organisations critical of the Fidesz government have allegedly been selectively denied legal status and funding.<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\"Bayer\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/orbans-war-of-attrition-against-churches/|title=Orb\u00e1n's 'war of attrition' against churches|last=Bayer|first=Lili|date=7 November 2016|work=Politico|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> Religious institutions had historically dependent upon significant government subsidies. Loss of legal status would result in the loss of government and taxpayer funds. The law was deemed a violation of religious freedom by the [[European Court of Human Rights]] in 2014, but the Hungarian government refused to properly amend it. The government asserted the reform was necessary to address widespread abuse of the system while some government officials said the law needed to be amended but blamed a lack of cooperation from the opposition.<ref name=\"Bayer\"/>\n\n=== Cronyism ===\nThe Fidesz government has been accused of corruption<ref name=\":25\" /> and of fostering a \"clique of loyal oligarchs\".<ref name=\":2\" /> Hungary's corruption assessment has worsened significantly according to [[World Bank]] data despite a regional trend in the opposite direction.<ref name=\":31\" /> During the first 6 years of the Fidesz government, 5 of Orb\u00e1n's closest associates were awarded ~5% of all public procurement contracts, totaling $2.5bn.<ref name=\":31\" /> The Fidesz government has been accused of diverting billions of euros of EU and federal funds toward loyal allies and relatives (with those who fell out of favour with the party also ceasing being granted the lucrative contracts).<ref name=\":34\"/><ref name=\":33\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/03/world/europe/eu-farm-subsidy-hungary.html|title=The Money Farmers: How Oligarchs and Populists Milk the E.U. for Millions|last=Gebrekidan|first=Selam|date=2019-11-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-07|last2=Apuzzo|first2=Matt|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Novak|first3=Benjamin}}</ref> The EU anti-fraud agency has launched multiple investigation into misuse of EU funds by people close to PM Orb\u00e1n, including a company owned by Orb\u00e1n's son-in-law.<ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":28\"/><ref name=\":29\"/> The government has been accused of punishing non-loyal businesspeople with punitive taxes and regulation.<ref name=\":33\" /><ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" /> A Hungarian economist described the government's economic shenanigans as \"authoritarian capitalism\"<ref name=\":33\" /> while some Hungarian and international experts have described post-2010 Hungary as a [[kleptocracy]].<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />\n\n=== Immigration ===\nThe [[European Court of Human Rights]] has rebuked the Fidesz-led Hungarian government for failing to provide food to asylum seekers residing in Hungarian detention centres.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-europe-migrants-hungary-food-idUSKCN1L81R8|title=European rights court says Hungary must feed asylum seekers on border|date=23 August 2018|agency=Reuters|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe \"Stop Soros\" law outlawing support or promotion of illegal immigration has been criticized for being so vague as to potentially criminalize providing humanitarian aid to immigrants; giving food for undocumented migrants on the street, distributing information about the asylum process, providing migrants with financial assistance, or even attending political rallies in support of immigrants' rights.<ref name=\"Beauchamp\"/><ref name=\":27\" />\n\nThe Fidesz government has been accused of using an illusory spectre of immigration for its political gain; despite decreasing numbers of migrants making their way into the region, the government escalated its rhetoric on immigration.<ref name=\"It happened there: how democracy died in Hungary\" />\n\nDue to socioeconomic factors, the Orb\u00e1n government increased the extent of economic migration into the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hungary-loudly-opposed-to-immigration-opens-doors-to-more-foreign-workers-11567944008|title=Hungary, Loudly Opposed to Immigration, Opens Doors to More Foreign Workers|last=Hungary|first=Bojan Pancevski in Budapest and Adam Bihari in M\u00f3r|website=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":36\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.infomigrants.net/en/post/19841/in-orban-s-hungary-more-migrants-due-to-labor-shortage|title=In Orban's Hungary, more migrants due to labor shortage|date=30 September 2019|website=InfoMigrants|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> despite Orb\u00e1n's previous statements denouncing foreign workers. Reportedly, the government's anti-immigration sentiment has fueled social strife between Hungarian and foreign workers. Hungarian trade unions also voiced fears that the increase in low-wage foreign labourers could suppress overall wages.<ref name=\":36\" />\n\n=== Conflict with the EU ===\nIn September 2018, the [[European Parliament]] voted to suspend Hungary's voting rights within the EU, accusing it of breaching democratic norms and EU's core values.<ref name=\":9\"/><ref name=\":4\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/12/world/europe/hungary-eu-viktor-orban.html|title=Hungary's Democracy Is in Danger, E.U. Parliament Decides|last=Kingsley|first=Patrick|date=12 September 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 March 2019|last2=Erlanger|first2=Steven|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45498514|title=Hungary faces unprecedented EU action|date=12 September 2018|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> The move was the first step in a procedural process to sanction the Hungarian government that could result in the country losing its EU voting rights were it to be successfully completed, marking the first instance of the punitive process' use in the history of the EU.<ref name=\":4\" /> \"A report detailing Hungary's alleged breaches of democratic norms, which was used to justify European Parliament's disciplinary action, cited violations including weakening media plurality, crackdowns on civil society and moves towards limiting educational freedom.\"<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nMembers of the Hungarian government challenged the legality of the vote saying that the just made decision of not counting abstentions as votes cast is irregular and because only by violating rules was it possible to reach the necessary two-thirds majority. [[P\u00e9ter Szijj\u00e1rt\u00f3]], Hungary's FM stated \"it's a collection of qualified lies\" and they will challenge the vote with the EP's leadership<ref>{{cite web |url=https://euobserver.com/political/142818 |title=EP triggers sanctions procedure, Hungary calls 'fraud' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=12 September 2018 |work=EUobserver}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/04/26/eu-parliament-s-hungary-report-a-collection-of-lies-says-budapest |title=EU parliament's Hungary report a 'collection of lies,' says FM |last=Embling  |first=Damon |website=euronews.com |publisher=euronews}}</ref>\n\nOn policy grounds, Orb\u00e1n and his government also came into conflict with the EU by voicing support for the possible reintroduction of the death penalty within Hungary (EU rules prohibit the death penalty for all member states) and by clashing with the EU over the handling of the [[European migrant crisis]].<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/apr/29/hungary-pm-death-penalty-work-camps-for-immigrants-viktor-orban|title=Hungary PM: bring back death penalty and build work camps for immigrants|last=Traynor|first=Ian|date=29 April 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" />\n\nFidesz has also come into conflict with the EPP; after 12 member parties called for Fidesz's expulsion or suspension, Fidesz's membership was suspended by a mutual agreement.<ref name=\"Fid-EPP\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Politics this week |url=https://www.economist.com/the-world-this-week/2019/03/23/politics-this-week |accessdate=24 March 2019 |work=The Economist |date=23 March 2019 |page=7 |quote=\"The European People's Party, a grouping of centre-right parties at the European Parliament, voted to suspend Fidesz, Hungary's ruling party, as a protest against what many in the parliament believe are repeated attempts by the government to undermine the rule of law\"}}</ref><ref>http://hungarymatters.hu/2019/03/21/fidesz-unilaterally-suspends-rights-in-epp/</ref> Orb\u00e1n has also suggested that Fidesz is considering leaving the EPP voluntarily.<ref name=\"Hungary's Fidesz could consider alliance with Polish ruling party\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/08/hungary-orban--fidesz-could-quit-epp-amid-anti-juncker-row|title=Hungary's Orb\u00e1n says Fidesz could quit EPP amid anti-Juncker row|last=Reuters|date=8 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=14 March 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nFidesz has also been condemned by EU politicians and institutions for launching a government campaign involving ads, billboards, and letters sent to all citizens suggesting that EU's immigration policy is being controlled by Soros (who is depicted standing behind and smiling with [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] with the subtext reading \"\u2018You have the right to know what Brussels is planning to do ... compulsory relocation quotas\").<ref name=\"Rankin\"/><ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":18\" /> In response to the political ad campaign, the leader of the EPP has demanded Orb\u00e1n apologize for and renounce the criticism levied against EU by him and his party or face Fidesz's suspension from the EPP.<ref name=\"Reuters\"/>\n\nOrb\u00e1n was on multiple occasions also rebuffed by various institutions of the European Union. In a speech, Orb\u00e1n boasted to his supporters that he had been out-maneuvering EU institutions by implementing contentious policies without excessively provoking them and incurring only painless criticism instead of any real push-back (a tactic he has dubbed \"the dance of the peacock\").<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":34\" />\n\n=== Anti-government protests ===\n\n==== Internet tax protests ====\nAfter the government revealed a plan to tax internet users' traffic in 2014, up to 100,000 people [[2014 Hungarian Internet tax protests|gathered in a series of protests]]. Facing widespread opposition, the government reduced the proposed tax rates, however, discontent and protests continued. The design of the tax was also criticized by the [[European Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hungary-internet-protest-idUSKBN0IH29M20141029|title=Around 100,000 Hungarians rally for democracy as internet tax hits...|date=29 October 2014|agency=Reuters|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref> The plan was eventually scrapped by the government entirely.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29846285|title=Hungary scraps controversial web tax|date=31 October 2014|access-date=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Overtime law ====\nIn late 2018, the government amended the labour code to increase maximum overtime from 250h to 400h, and delaying the employee compensation deadline from 1 to 3 years. In some instances, the law would also allow employers to compensate workers at the regular hourly rate for overtime work. The changes were motivated by the country's labour shortage, and sparked a wave of protests and opposition.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/22/world/europe/hungary-slave-law.html|title=What Is Hungary's \u2018Slave Law,\u2019 and Why Has It Provoked Opposition?|last=Karasz|first=Palko|date=22 December 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=13 March 2019|last2=Kingsley|first2=Patrick|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Opponents dubbed the proposed changes the \"''Slave law''\". The government says the labor reforms are necessary to provide much-needed support for businesses struggling to cope with a shortage of workers. The jobless rate in Hungary has dropped to a near all-time low of 3.7 percent, while the number of unfilled jobs has reportedly doubled to a record high in the last three years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/11/orban-hungarys-new-slave-law-risks-first-general-strike-since-fall-of-communism.html|title=Orban: Hungary's new slave law risks first general strike since fall of communism|last=Meredith|first=Sam|date=11 January 2019|publisher=CNBC|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe protests that initially opposed the \"Slave law\" soon evolved to also voice opposition to the nature and actions of the ruling government in general, with multiple opposition parties joining the protests in solidarity. The protests, with the number of attendants peaking at about 15,000, have been one of the most significant shows of public opposition to the Fidesz government, but have fallen far short of the wast political support the party enjoys within Hungary. A government spokesman dismissed the notion of popular support for the protests.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Leaders ==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!\n! Image\n! Name\n! Entered office\n! Left office\n! Length of Leadership\n! Note\n|-\n! 1\n| [[File:Viktor Orb\u00e1n 1997.jpg|60px]]\n| [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]]\n| 18 April 1993\n| 29 January 2000\n| {{ayd|1993|04|18|2000|01|29}} \n| Prime Minister, 1998\u20132002\n|-\n! 2\n| [[File:L\u00e1szl\u00f3 K\u00f6v\u00e9r Senate of Poland 01.JPG|60px]]\n| [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 K\u00f6v\u00e9r]]\n| 29 January 2000\n| 6 May 2001\n| {{ayd|2000|01|29|2001|05|06}} \n| \n|-\n! 3\n| [[File:Pokorni Zoltan 2008-10-23 (crop).JPG|60px]]\n| [[Zolt\u00e1n Pokorni]]\n| 6 May 2001\n| 3 July 2002\n| {{ayd|2001|05|06|2002|07|03}} \n|\n|-\n! 4\n| [[File:Ader Janos.jpg|60px]]\n| [[J\u00e1nos \u00c1der]] \n| 3 July 2002\n| 17 May 2003\n| {{ayd|2002|07|03|2003|05|17}} \n| \n|-\n! 5\n| [[File:Viktor Orban.jpg|60px]]\n| [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]]\n| 17 May 2003\n| ''Incumbent''\n| {{ayd|2003|5|17}}\n| Prime Minister, 2010\u2013present\n|-\n|}\n\n==Electoral results==\n\n=== National Assembly ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:60px;\"| Election\n! colspan=\"3\"| Votes\n! colspan=\"2\"| Seats\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:30px;\"| Rank\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:145px;\"|Government\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Leader\n|-\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| #\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| %\n! style=\"width:48px;\"| \u00b1[[Percentage point|pp]]\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| #\n! style=\"width:40px;\"| +/\u2212\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[1990 Hungarian parliamentary election|1990]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 439,481\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 8.95%\n| rowspan=\"2\" | \u2013\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{Composition bar|22|386|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | \u00b10\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 5th\n| {{no2|[[Hungarian Democratic Forum|MDF]]\u2013[[Independent Smallholders, Agrarian Workers and Civic Party|FKgP]]\u2013[[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|KDNP]]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]]\n|-\n| {{no2|[[Hungarian Democratic Forum|MDF]]\u2013[[United Smallholders' Party|EKGP]]\u2013[[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|KDNP]]}}\n|-\n! [[1994 Hungarian parliamentary election|1994]]\n| 379,295\n| 7.02%\n| {{decrease}}1.93\n| {{Composition bar|20|386|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 2\n| 6th\n| {{no2|[[Hungarian Socialist Party|MSZP]]\u2013[[Alliance of Free Democrats|SZDSZ]] Supermajority}}\n| Viktor Orb\u00e1n\n|-\n! [[1998 Hungarian parliamentary election|1998]]\n| 1,263,522\n| 28.18%\n| {{increase}}21.16\n| {{Composition bar|148|386|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 128\n| '''1st'''\n| {{yes2|Fidesz-[[Independent Smallholders, Agrarian Workers and Civic Party|FKgP]]-[[Hungarian Democratic Forum|MDF]]}}\n| Viktor Orb\u00e1n\n|-\n! [[2002 Hungarian parliamentary election|2002]]<sup>1</sup>\n| 2,306,763\n| 41.07%\n| {{increase}}13.89\n| {{Composition bar|164|386|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 16\n| 2nd\n| {{no2|[[Hungarian Socialist Party|MSZP]]\u2013[[Alliance of Free Democrats|SZDSZ]]}}\n| Viktor Orb\u00e1n\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[2006 Hungarian parliamentary election|2006]]<sup>2</sup>\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2,272,979\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 42.03%\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{increase}}0.96\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{Composition bar|141|386|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{decrease}} 23\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2nd\n| {{no2|[[Hungarian Socialist Party|MSZP]]\u2013[[Alliance of Free Democrats|SZDSZ]]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Viktor Orb\u00e1n\n|-\n| {{no2|[[Hungarian Socialist Party|MSZP]] Minority}}\n|-\n! [[2010 Hungarian parliamentary election|2010]]<sup>2</sup>\n| 2,706,292\n| 52.73%\n| {{increase}}10.70\n| {{Composition bar|227|386|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 86\n| '''1st'''\n| {{yes2|Fidesz\u2013[[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|KDNP]] Supermajority}}\n| Viktor Orb\u00e1n\n|-\n! [[2014 Hungarian parliamentary election|2014]]<sup>2</sup>\n| 2,264,486\n| 44.87%\n| {{decrease}}7.86\n| {{Composition bar|117|199|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 110\n| '''1st'''\n| {{yes2|Fidesz\u2013[[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|KDNP]] Supermajority}}\n| Viktor Orb\u00e1n\n|-\n! [[2018 Hungarian parliamentary election|2018]]<sup>2</sup>\n| 2,824,206\n| 49.27%\n| {{increase}}4.40\n| {{Composition bar|117|199|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{steady}} 0\n| '''1st'''\n| {{yes2|Fidesz\u2013[[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|KDNP]] Supermajority}}\n| Viktor Orb\u00e1n\n|}\n<small><sup>1</sup> Joint list with [[Hungarian Democratic Forum]] (MDF)</small>\n\n<small><sup>2</sup> Joint list with [[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|Christian Democratic People's Party]] (KDNP)</small>\n\n====Single member constituencies voting consistently for Fidesz====\nThe SMCs shown on the image have voted for Fidesz ever since 1998. SMCs with a paler hue of orange elected FKGP candidates in 1998, as part of a pact between the two parties.\n\n[[File:Consecutive Fidesz SMCs.png|thumb|center|500px|Consistently Fidesz SMCs (inset shows Budapest)]]\n{{Clear}}\n\nIn January 2010, [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 K\u00f6v\u00e9r]], head of the party's national board, told reporters the party was aiming at winning a two-thirds majority at the parliamentary elections in April. He noted that Fidesz had a realistic chance to win a landslide. Concerning the radical nationalist [[Jobbik]] party's gaining ground K\u00f6v\u00e9r said it was a \"lamentably negative\" tendency, adding that it was rooted in the ''\"disaster government\"'' of the Socialist Party and its former liberal ally Free Democrats.<ref>{{cite web |author=MTI |url=http://www.politics.hu/20100129/opposition-fidesz-aims-at-twothirds-majority |title=Opposition Fidesz aims at two-thirds majority |publisher=Politics.hu |accessdate=17 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311112636/http://www.politics.hu/20100129/opposition-fidesz-aims-at-twothirds-majority/ |archive-date=11 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===European Parliament===\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Election year\n! # of overall votes\n! % of overall vote\n! # of overall seats won\n! +/-\n! Notes\n|-\n! [[2004 European Parliament election in Hungary|2004]]\n| 1,457,750\n| 47.4% ('''1st''')\n| {{Composition bar|12|24|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| \n| \n|-\n! [[2009 European Parliament election in Hungary|2009]]<sup>1</sup>\n| 1,632,309\n| 56.36% ('''1st''')\n| {{Composition bar|13|22|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n|\n|-\n! [[2014 European Parliament election in Hungary|2014]]<sup>1</sup>\n| 1,193,991\n| 51.48% ('''1st''')\n| {{Composition bar|11|21|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{decrease}} 2\n|\n|-\n! [[2019 European Parliament election in Hungary|2019]]<sup>1</sup>\n| 1,824,220\n| 52.56% ('''1st''')\n| {{Composition bar|12|21|hex={{Fidesz/meta/color}}}}\n| {{increase}} 1\n|\n|}\n<sup>1</sup> <small>Joint list with [[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|Christian Democratic People's Party]] (KDNP)</small>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{commons category|Fidesz}}\n*[http://www.fidesz.hu/ Fidesz \u2013 Hungarian Civic Union] Official website\n*[http://www.epp.eu/countryPg.asp?cid=12 Fidesz page on the website of the European People's Party]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060310004229/http://www.fideszfrakcio.hu/index.php?CikkID=10909&FIDESZSESSID=d777505ada9e30c9dc3a785cfa89d5a8 Speech delivered by Mr Viktor Orban at the 17th Congress of Fidesz upon his election as president of Fidesz \u2013 Hungarian Civic Union, 17 May 2003] (from Google's cache)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051129071015/http://www.fideszfrakcio.hu/index.php?CikkID=5350&FIDESZSESSID=3a4bab2f824